# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: habitat-destruction
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:habitat-destruction/7-billion-actions] Estimated and projected populations of the world and its continents (except Antarctica) from 1950.
[src:habitat-destruction/7-billion-actions] The shaded regions correspond to the range of projections by the United Nations Department of Economic and Social Affairs.
[src:habitat-destruction/7-billion-actions] The Day of Seven Billion, October 31, 2011, is the day that has been officially designated by the United Nations Population Fund (UNFPA) as the approximate day on which the total world population reached a population of seven billion people.
[src:habitat-destruction/7-billion-actions] United Nations Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon spoke at the United Nations building in New York City on this milestone in the size of world population about the issues that it will raise, along with promoting 7 Billion Actions.
[src:habitat-destruction/7-billion-actions] The 7 Billion Actions Campaign aims to raise awareness of key population issues such as reproductive health, poverty, women empowerment, youth, environment sustainability, ageing, and urbanization, by encouraging people to take action and recommit to humanity.
[src:habitat-destruction/7-billion-actions] The campaign will count and showcase 7 billion online and offline actions that tell the story of the people behind the number and the connections they share with each other and the issues they each face.
[src:habitat-destruction/7-billion-actions] The 7 Billion Actions Campaign centers on highlighting individuals and organizations making a significant impact and creating innovative solutions in the 7 key issues identified as most imperative for the growing global population.
[src:habitat-destruction/7-billion-actions] 7BillionActions.org: Showcases stories, interviews, and news.
[src:habitat-destruction/7-billion-actions] In-depth platform to help individuals connect and take action with efforts taking place near them or across the globe.
[src:habitat-destruction/7-billion-actions] Interactive data visualizations highlighting challenges and solutions.
[src:habitat-destruction/7-billion-actions] I Count: An online and SMS/mobile effort allowing anyone on Earth to step forward to be counted as one of the 7 billion and share what issues matters most to them.
[src:habitat-destruction/7-billion-actions] These are but a few of the important resources being created to facilitate connection and collaboration.
[src:habitat-destruction/7-billion-actions] World Story Book: A community-created collection of photos, text, audio, and video that tell the stories of struggle and success of the people behind the number.
[src:habitat-destruction/7-billion-actions] 7Billion Hashtag (#7Billion): An ongoing social media conversation on Twitter, Facebook, and other major social media platforms (representing each major region) designed to help fuel awareness, engagement, and participation.
[src:habitat-destruction/7-billion-actions] IBM: As a way to celebrate its 100th anniversary, IBM is launching its Global Celebration of Service, a worldwide volunteer service initiative which calls for staff to donate their time and energy to specific social causes.
[src:habitat-destruction/7-billion-actions] 7 Billion Actions will be presented as one of the official programs which staff can support.
[src:habitat-destruction/7-billion-actions] As part of the new partnership, IBM volunteers will contribute their engineering, marketing, communications, social media and analytics expertise to help build the 7 Billion Actions campaign platform.
[src:habitat-destruction/7-billion-actions] crowdSPRING: crowdSPRING launched a series of design competitions to crowd source the official logo for the 7 Billion Actions Campaign.
[src:habitat-destruction/7-billion-actions] The first round of the competition drew over one thousand submissions and the winning design will become the 7 Billion Action Campaign's official global logo.
[src:habitat-destruction/7-billion-actions] The next phase will open voting to the public in order to select a group of regionally themed logos.
[src:habitat-destruction/7-billion-actions] Blog Talk Radio: Using their telephone-to-internet platform, the 7 Billion Actions Campaign will launch the Conversations for a World at 7 Billion channel to showcase a variety of audio programs discussing the topics and themes facing the 7 billion.
[src:habitat-destruction/7-billion-actions] People in different countries and regions will have the opportunity listen to and call into these programs and share their stories and actions.
[src:habitat-destruction/7-billion-actions] Playing for Change: The non-profit group the Playing for Change Foundation will partner with 7 Billion Actions to produce an official campaign song.
[src:habitat-destruction/abundance-ecology] In ecology, **local abundance** is the relative representation of a species in a particular ecosystem.
[src:habitat-destruction/abundance-ecology] It is usually measured as the number of individuals found per sample.
[src:habitat-destruction/abundance-ecology] The ratio of abundance of one species to one or multiple other species living in an ecosystem is referred to as relative species abundances.
[src:habitat-destruction/abundance-ecology] Both indicators are relevant for computing biodiversity.
[src:habitat-destruction/abundance-ecology] A variety of sampling methods are used to measure abundance.
[src:habitat-destruction/abundance-ecology] For larger animals, these may include spotlight counts, track counts and roadkill counts, as well as presence at monitoring stations.
[src:habitat-destruction/abundance-ecology] In many plant communities the abundances of plant species are measured by plant cover, i.e. the relative area covered by different plant species in a small plot.
[src:habitat-destruction/abundance-ecology] Abundance is in simplest terms usually measured by identifying and counting every individual of every species in a given sector.
[src:habitat-destruction/abundance-ecology] It is common for the distribution of species to be skewed so that a few species take up the bulk of individuals collected.
[src:habitat-destruction/abundance-ecology] Relative species abundance is calculated by dividing the number of species from one group by the total number of species from all groups.
[src:habitat-destruction/abundance-ecology] These measures are all a part of community ecology.
[src:habitat-destruction/abundance-ecology] Understanding patterns within a community is easy when the community has a relatively low number of species.
[src:habitat-destruction/abundance-ecology] However most communities do not have a low number of species.
[src:habitat-destruction/abundance-ecology] Measuring species abundance allows for understanding of how species are distributed within an ecosystem.
[src:habitat-destruction/abundance-ecology] For example, salt water marshes have an influx of sea water, causing only a few species which are adapted to be able to survive in both salt and fresh water to be abundant.
[src:habitat-destruction/abundance-ecology] Inversely in land locked wetlands, the species abundance is more evenly distributed among the species who live within the wetland.
[src:habitat-destruction/abundance-ecology] In most ecosystems in which abundance has been calculated, most often only a small number of species are abundant, while a large number are pretty rare.
[src:habitat-destruction/abundance-ecology] These abundant species are often generalists, with many rare species being specialists.
[src:habitat-destruction/abundance-ecology] High density of a species in multiple localities will usually lead to it being relatively abundant over all in an ecosystem.
[src:habitat-destruction/abundance-ecology] Therefore, high local abundance can be directly linked to high regional distribution.
[src:habitat-destruction/abundance-ecology] Species with high abundance are likely to have more offspring, and these offspring in turn are more likely to colonize a new sector of the ecosystem than a species which is less abundant.
[src:habitat-destruction/abundance-ecology] Thus begins a positive feedback loop leading to a species distribution in which a few "core species" are wide spread, and the other species are restricted and scarce known as satellite species.
[src:habitat-destruction/abundance-ecology] Species abundance distribution (SAD) is one of the main uses of this measurement.
[src:habitat-destruction/abundance-ecology] SAD is a measurement of how common, or rare species are within an ecosystem.
[src:habitat-destruction/abundance-ecology] This allows researchers to assess how different species are distributed throughout an ecosystem.
[src:habitat-destruction/abundance-ecology] SAD is one of the most basic measurements in ecology and is used very often, therefore many different methods of measurement and analysis have developed.
[src:habitat-destruction/abundance-ecology] There are several methods for measuring abundance.
[src:habitat-destruction/abundance-ecology] An example of this is Semi-Quantitive Abundance ratings.
[src:habitat-destruction/abundance-ecology] These are measurement methods which involve estimation based on viewing a specific area of a designated size.
[src:habitat-destruction/abundance-ecology] The two Semi-Quantitive Abundance ratings used are known as the D.A.F.O.R, and the A.C.F.O.R.
[src:habitat-destruction/abundance-ecology] These methods are useful for getting a rough estimate of the species abundance in a designated area (quadrant), but they are not exact or objective measurements.
[src:habitat-destruction/abundance-ecology] Therefore, if another method of measuring abundance is available, it should be used, as this will lead to more useful and quantifiable data.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Acid rain has been shown to have adverse impacts on forests, freshwaters, soils, microbes, insects and aquatic life-forms.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] In ecosystems, persistent acid rain negatively affects tree bark, leaving trees more susceptible to environmental stressors such as drought, fire, solar radiation, frost and pest infestation.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Acid rain is also capable of detrimenting soil composition by stripping it of nutrients such as calcium and magnesium which play a critical role in plant growth and maintaining healthy soil.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] In terms of human infrastructure, acid rain also causes the peeling of paint, corrosion of steel structures, and weathering of stone buildings and statues as well as having impacts on human health.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Some governments, including those in Europe and North America, have made efforts since the 1970s to reduce the release of sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxide into the atmosphere through air pollution regulations such as the US Clean Air Act and the EU Ambient Air Quality Directive.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] These efforts have had positive results due to the widespread research on acid rain starting in the 1960s and the publicized information on its harmful effects.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The main source of sulfur and nitrogen compounds that result in acid rain are anthropogenic, but nitrogen oxides can also be produced naturally by lightning strikes and sulfur dioxide is produced by volcanic eruptions.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Acid rain is rain with a pH less than 5.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] A variety of natural and human-made sources contribute to the acidity of precipitations.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] For example nitric acid is produced by electric discharges in the atmosphere such as in lightnings.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The usual anthropogenic sources of acid deposition are sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxide.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] They react with water (as does carbon dioxide) to give solutions with pH < 5.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Occasional pH readings in rain and fog water of well below 2.4 have been reported in industrialized areas.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Acid rain was first systematically studied in Europe in the 1960s, in the United States and Canada in 1970s, and in India in the late 1980s.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The corrosive effect of polluted, acidic air of London on limestone and marble was noted in the 17th century by John Evelyn, who remarked upon the poor condition of the Arundel marbles.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Since the Industrial Revolution, emissions of sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxides into the atmosphere have increased.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] In 1852, Robert Angus Smith was the first to show the relationship between acid rain and atmospheric pollution in Manchester, England.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Smith coined the term "acid rain" in 1872.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] As soon as the 1960s, European scientists began widely observing and studying the phenomenon.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] In 1955 two Swedish scientists had already quoted that "the precipitation over Sweden as a whole is definitely more acid than the CO2 equilibrium alone would permit".
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] At first, the main focus in this research laid on local effects of acid rain.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Waldemar Christofer Brøgger was the first to acknowledge long-distance transportation of pollutants crossing borders from the United Kingdom to Norway.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Near a century later this problem was systematically studied by Brynjulf Ottar in the 1970s.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Ottar's work was strongly influenced by Swedish soil scientist Svante Odén, who had drawn widespread attention to Europe's acid rain problem in popular newspapers and wrote a landmark paper on the subject in 1968.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The earliest report about acid rain in the United States came from chemical evidence gathered from Hubbard Brook Valley; public awareness of acid rain in the US increased in the 1970s after *The New York Times* reported on these findings.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] In 1972, a group of scientists, including Gene Likens, discovered the rain that was deposited at White Mountains of New Hampshire was acidic.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The pH of the sample was measured to be 4.03 at Hubbard Brook.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The Hubbard Brook Ecosystem Study followed up with a series of research studies that analyzed the environmental effects of acid rain.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The alumina from soils neutralized acid rain that mixed with stream water at Hubbard Brook.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The result of this research indicated that the chemical reaction between acid rain and aluminium leads to an increasing rate of soil weathering.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Experimental research examined the effects of increased acidity in streams on ecological species.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] In 1980, scientists modified the acidity of Norris Brook, New Hampshire, and observed the change in species' behaviors.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] There was a decrease in species diversity, an increase in community dominants, and a reduction in the food web complexity.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] In 1980, the US Congress passed an Acid Deposition Act.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] This Act established an 18-year assessment and research program under the direction of the National Acid Precipitation Assessment Program (NAPAP).
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] NAPAP enlarged a network of monitoring sites to determine how acidic precipitation was, seeking to determine long-term trends, and established a network for dry deposition.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Using a statistically based sampling design, NAPAP quantified the effects of acid rain on a regional basis by targeting research and surveys to identify and quantify the impact of acid precipitation on freshwater and terrestrial ecosystems.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] NAPAP also assessed the effects of acid rain on historical buildings, monuments, and building materials.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] It also funded extensive studies on atmospheric processes and potential control programs.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] From the start, policy advocates from all sides attempted to influence NAPAP activities to support their particular policy advocacy efforts, or to disparage those of their opponents.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] For the US Government's scientific enterprise, a significant impact of NAPAP were lessons learned in the assessment process and in environmental research management to a relatively large group of scientists, program managers, and the public.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] In 1981, the National Academy of Sciences was looking into research about the controversial issues regarding acid rain, in particular the role of fossil fuel combustion.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] President Ronald Reagan dismissed the issues of acid rain until his personal visit to Canada and confirmed that the Canadian border suffered from the drifting pollution from smokestacks originating in the US Midwest.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Reagan honored the agreement to Canadian Prime Minister Pierre Trudeau's enforcement of anti-pollution regulation.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] In 1982, Reagan commissioned William Nierenberg to serve on the National Science Board.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Nierenberg selected scientists including Gene Likens to serve on a panel to draft a report on acid rain.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] In 1983, the panel of scientists came up with a draft report, which concluded that acid rain is a real problem and solutions should be sought.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] White House Office of Science and Technology Policy reviewed the draft report and sent Fred Singer's suggestions of the report, which cast doubt on the anthropic causes of acid rain.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The panelists revealed rejections against Singer's positions and submitted the report to Nierenberg in April.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] In May 1983, the House of Representatives voted against legislation controlling sulfur emissions.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] There was a debate about whether Nierenberg delayed the release of the report.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Nierenberg denied the saying about his suppression of the report and stated that it was withheld after the House's vote because it was not ready to be published.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] In 1991, the US National Acid Precipitation Assessment Program (NAPAP) provided its first assessment of acid rain in the United States.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] It reported that 5% of New England lakes were acidic, with sulfates being the most common problem.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] They noted that 2% of the lakes could no longer support Brook Trout, and 6% of the lakes were unsuitable for the survival of many minnow species.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Subsequent *Reports to Congress* have documented chemical changes in soil and freshwater ecosystems, nitrogen saturation, soil nutrient decreases, episodic acidification, regional haze, and damage to historical monuments.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Meanwhile, in 1990, the US Congress passed a series of amendments to the Clean Air Act.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Title IV of these amendments established a cap and trade system designed to control emissions of sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxides.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Both these emissions proved to cause a significant problem for U.S. citizens and their access to healthy, clean air.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Title IV called for a total reduction of about 10 million tons of SO2 emissions from power plants, close to a 50% reduction.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Phase I began in 1995 and limited sulfur dioxide emissions from 110 of the largest power plants to 8.7 million tons of sulfur dioxide.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] One power plant in New England (Merrimack) was in Phase I.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Four other plants (Newington, Mount Tom, Brayton Point, and Salem Harbor) were added under other program provisions.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Phase II began in 2000 and affects most of the power plants in the country.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] On March 10, 2005, the EPA issued the Clean Air Interstate Rule (CAIR).
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] This rule provides states with a solution to the problem of power plant pollution that drifts from one state to another.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] CAIR will permanently cap emissions of SO2 and NOx in the eastern United States.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] CAIR hoped to reduce SO2 emissions in 28 eastern states and the District of Columbia by over 70% and NOx emissions by over 60% from 2003 levels.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] CAIR was replaced by the Cross-State Air Pollution Rule (CSAPR), as of 1 January 2015.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Overall, the program's cap and trade program has been successful in achieving its goals.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Since the 1990s, SO2 emissions have dropped 40%, and according to the Pacific Research Institute, acid rain levels have dropped 65% since 1976.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Conventional regulation was used in the European Union, which saw a decrease of over 70% in SO2 emissions during the same period.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] In 2007, total SO2 emissions were 8.9 million tons, achieving the program's long-term goal ahead of the 2010 statutory deadline.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] In 2007 the EPA estimated that by 2010, the overall costs of complying with the program for businesses and consumers would be $1 billion to $2 billion a year, only one-fourth of what was initially predicted.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Forbes says: "In 2010, by which time the cap and trade system had been augmented by the George W.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The term citizen science can be traced back as far as January 1989 to a campaign by the Audubon Society to measure acid rain, with 280 volunteers nationwide, all members of the Audubon Society, making a one-year commitment to collect and measure the pH of precipitation samples.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Canadian Harold Harvey was among the first to research a "dead" lake.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] In 1972, he and Richard Beamish documented the gradual deterioration of fish stocks in 60 lakes in Killarney Park in Ontario, which they had been studying systematically since 1966.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] In the 1970s and 80s, acid rain was a major topic of research at the Experimental Lakes Area (ELA) in Northwestern Ontario, Canada.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Researchers added sulfuric acid to whole lakes in controlled ecosystem experiments to simulate the effects of acid rain.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Because its remote conditions allowed for whole-ecosystem experiments, research at the ELA showed that the effect of acid rain on fish populations started at concentrations much lower than those observed in laboratory experiments.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] In the context of a complete food web, fish populations crashed earlier than when acid rain had direct toxic effects to the fish because the acidity led to crashes in prey populations (e.g. mysids).
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] As experimental acid inputs were reduced, fish populations and lake ecosystems recovered at least partially, although invertebrate populations have still not completely returned to the baseline conditions.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] This research showed both that acidification was linked to declining fish populations and that the effects could be reversed if sulfuric acid emissions decreased, and influenced policy in Canada and the United States.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] In 1985, seven Canadian provinces (all except British Columbia, Alberta, and Saskatchewan) and the federal government signed the Eastern Canada Acid Rain Program.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The provinces agreed to limit their combined sulfur dioxide emissions to 2.3 million tonnes by 1994.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The US-Canada Air Quality Agreement was signed in 1991.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] In 1998, all federal, provincial, and territorial Ministers of Energy and Environment signed The Canada-Wide Acid Rain Strategy for Post-2000, which was designed to protect lakes that are more sensitive than those protected by earlier policies.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Acid rain was first reported in Mumbai (then Bombay) in 1974.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Acid rain has been a reported cause of decrease in soil pH, especially in the northeast region, as well as the coastal regions of Karnataka, Kerala, Odisha, Bihar, and West Bengal.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The spread of acid rain over India was first studied by a team of researchers in 1989.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Increased risk might be posed by the expected rise in total sulphur emissions from 4,400 kilotonnes (kt) in 1990 to 6,500 kt in 2000, 10,900 kt in 2010 and 18,500 in 2020.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Damage to Taj Mahal is a popular example of acid rain's corrosive effect in India.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] India is the largest sulphur emitter, mostly from coal-fired power plants.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] On 11 July 2025, the Indian government changed its own rules, exempting most coal-fired power plants from installing technology to reduce sulphur dioxide (SO2) emissions, reversing a key environmental policy launched in 2015 to cut sulphur emissions.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] In China, concern about the possible effects of acid rain emerged later than in Europe and North America.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The first reports in the international literature regarding acid rain in China appeared in the 1980s.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] A major cause of acid rain in China is the extensive use of coal, which in 2004 accounted for 69% of the energy production.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] However, a great need still exists for better monitoring of the environmental situation in China to support policy development and follow-up on emission reduction measures.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The most important gas which leads to acidification is sulfur dioxide.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] However, emissions of nitrogen oxides (NOx) and ammonia which are further oxidized to form nitric acid are of increasing importance due to stricter controls on emissions of sulfur compounds and the near absence of control on acid rain gasses emitted by intensive farming.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] 70 Tg(S) per year in the form of SO2 comes from fossil fuel combustion and industry, 2.8 Tg(S) from wildfires, and 7–8 Tg(S) per year from volcanoes.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The principal natural phenomena that contribute acid-producing gases to the atmosphere are emissions from volcanoes.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Acid-producing gases are also created by biological processes that occur in wetlands and the oceans.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The major biological source of atmospheric sulfur compounds is dimethyl sulfide.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Nitric acid is also produced by electrical activity in the atmosphere such as lightning.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Despite its toxicity, and negative effects of low pH, nitric acid in rainwater is an important source of fixed nitrogen for plant life.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Acidic sulfate deposits associated with tephra have been detected in glacial ice thousands of years old in remote parts of the globe, suggesting that volcanism was the main agent of rain acidification before the Anthropocene.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The principal cause of present-day acid rain is sulfur and nitrogen compounds from human sources, such as coal-fired power stations, animal agriculture, fertilizers, steel mills, and motor vehicles.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Power plants account for a quarter of nitrogen oxides (NOx) and two-thirds of sulfur dioxide within the atmosphere.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Industrial acid rain is still a substantial problem in China and Russia and areas downwind from them.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] These areas all burn sulfur-containing coal to generate heat and electricity.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The problem of acid rain has not only increased with population and industrial growth, but has become more widespread.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The use of tall smokestacks to reduce local pollution has contributed to the spread of acid rain by releasing gases into regional atmospheric circulation; dispersal from these taller stacks causes pollutants to be carried farther, causing widespread ecological damage.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Often deposition occurs a considerable distance downwind of the emissions, with mountainous regions tending to receive the greatest deposition because of their higher rainfall and direct contact with long-distance transported clouds.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] An example of this effect is the low pH of rain which falls in Scandinavia.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Acid rain falls at a pH value of roughly 4, making it harmful to consume for humans, plants, microbes and animals.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] When these low pH levels fall in specific regions, they not only affect the environment but also human health.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] With acidic pH levels in humans comes hair loss, low urinary pH, severe mineral deficiency, constipation, and many cases of chronic disorders like fibromyalgia and basal-cell carcinoma.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Combustion of fuels and smelting of some ores produce sulfur dioxide and nitric oxides (NOx).
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] They are converted into sulfuric acid and nitric acid by photochemical reactions in the troposphere.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The detailed mechanisms depend on the presence water and traces of iron and manganese.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] A number of oxidants are capable of these reactions aside from O2, these include ozone, hydrogen peroxide, and oxygen.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Wet deposition of acids occurs when any form of precipitation (e.g. rain, snow, fog) removes acids from the atmosphere and delivers them to the Earth's surface.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] This can result from the deposition of acids produced in the raindrops or by the precipitation removing the acids either in clouds or below clouds.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Wet removal of both gases and aerosols are both of importance for wet deposition.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Acid deposition also occurs via dry deposition in the absence of precipitation.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] This can be responsible for as much as 20 to 60% of total acid deposition.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] This occurs when particles and gases stick to the ground, plants or other surfaces.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Acid rain has been shown to have adverse impacts on forests, freshwaters and soils, killing terrestrial and aquatic life-forms as well as causing damage to buildings and having impacts on human health.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Sulfuric acid and nitric acid have multiple impacts on aquatic ecosystems, including acidification, increased nitrogen and aluminium content, and alteration of biogeochemical processes.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Both the lower pH and higher aluminium concentrations in surface water that occur as a result of acid rain can cause damage to fish and other aquatic animals as well as to microbes and plants.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] At pH lower than 5 most fish eggs will not hatch and pH lower than 4 will kill adult fish.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] As lakes and rivers become more acidic, biodiversity is reduced, while it is less affected in regions where freshwater is naturally acid.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Acid rain has eliminated insect life and some fish species, including the brook trout in some lakes, streams, and creeks in geographically sensitive areas, such as the Adirondack Mountains of the United States.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] However, the extent to which acid rain contributes directly or indirectly via runoff from the catchment to lake and river acidity (i.e., depending on characteristics of the surrounding watershed) is variable.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The United States Environmental Protection Agency's (EPA) website states: "Of the lakes and streams surveyed, acid rain caused acidity in 75% of the acidic lakes and about 50% of the acidic streams".
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Lakes hosted by silicate basement rocks are more acidic than lakes within limestone or other basement rocks with a carbonate composition (i.e. marble) due to buffering effects by carbonate minerals, even with the same amount of acid rain.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Soil biology and chemistry can be seriously damaged by acid rain.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Some microbes are unable to tolerate changes to low pH and are killed.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The enzymes of these microbes are denatured (changed in shape so they no longer function) by the acid, with attending collapse in soil functions (e.g. decomposition).
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The hydronium ions of acid rain also mobilize toxins, such as aluminium, and leach away essential nutrients and minerals such as magnesium.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Soil chemistry can be dramatically changed when base cations, such as calcium and magnesium, are leached by acid rain, thereby affecting sensitive tree species, such as sugar maple (*Acer saccharum*).
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Impacts of acidic water and soil acidification on plants could be minor or in most cases major.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Most minor cases which do not result in fatality of plant life can be attributed to the plants being less susceptible to acidic conditions and/or the acid rain being less potent.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] However, even in minor cases, the plant will eventually die due to the acidic water lowering the plant's natural pH.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Acidic water enters the plant and causes important plant minerals to dissolve and get carried away; which ultimately causes the plant to die of lack of minerals for nutrition.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] In major cases, which are more extreme, the same process of damage occurs as in minor cases, which is removal of essential minerals, but at a much quicker rate.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Likewise, acid rain that falls on soil and on plant leaves causes drying of the waxy leaf cuticle, which ultimately causes rapid water loss from the plant to the outside atmosphere and eventually results in death of the plant.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Soil acidification can lead to a decline in soil microbes as a result of a change in pH, which would have an adverse effect on plants due to their dependence on soil microbes to access nutrients.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] To see if a plant is being affected by soil acidification, one can closely observe the plant leaves.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] If the leaves are green and look healthy, the soil pH is normal and acceptable for plant life.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] But if the plant leaves have yellowing between the veins on their leaves, that means the plant is suffering from acidification and is unhealthy.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Moreover, a plant suffering from soil acidification cannot photosynthesize; the acid-water-induced process of drying out of the plant can destroy chloroplast organelles.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Without being able to photosynthesize, a plant cannot create nutrients for its own survival or oxygen for the survival of aerobic organisms, which affects most species on Earth and ultimately ends the purpose of the plant's existence.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] It has been suggested that the collapse of photosynthesis linked to acid rain (caused by the emission of sulfur oxide from intense volcanism) could have contributed to the Permian-Triassic mass extinction.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Adverse effects may be indirectly related to acid rain, like the acid's effects on soil (see above) or the high concentration of gaseous precursors to acid rain.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] High altitude forests are especially vulnerable as they are often surrounded by clouds and fog which are more acidic than rain.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Plants are capable of adapting to acid rain.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] On Jinyun Mountain, Chongqing, plant species were seen adapting to new environmental conditions.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The affects on the species ranged from being beneficial to detrimental.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] With natural rainfall or mild acid rainfall, the biochemical and physiological characteristics of plant seedlings were enhanced.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] However, once the pH decreases below the threshold of 3.5, the acid rain can no longer be beneficial and begins to have negative affects.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Acid rain can negatively impact photosynthesis in plant leaves, when leaves are exposed to a lower pH, photosynthesis is impacted due to the decline in chlorophyll.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Acid rain also has the ability to cause deformation to leaves at a cellular level, tissue scaring and changes to the stomatal, epidermis and mesophyll cells.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Additional impacts of acid rain includes a decline in cuticle thickness present on the leaf surface.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Because acid rain damages leaves, this directly impacts a plants ability to have a strong canopy cover, a decline in canopy cover can lead plants to be more vulnerable to diseases.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Dead or dying trees (forest dieback) often appear in areas impacted by acid rain, although other factors such as drought stress linked to global warming cannot be excluded, too.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Acid rain causes aluminium to leach from the soil, posing risks to both plant and animal life.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Furthermore, it strips the soil of critical minerals and nutrients necessary for tree growth.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] At higher altitudes, acidic fog and clouds can deplete nutrients from tree foliage, leading to discolored or dead leaves and needles, with broadleaved species tending to be more sentitive than conifers.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] This depletion compromises the trees' ability to absorb sunlight, weakening them and diminishing their capacity to endure cold conditions.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Other plants can also be damaged by acid rain, but the effect on food crops is (or should be) minimized by the application of lime and fertilizers to replace lost nutrients.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] In cultivated areas, limestone may also be added to increase the ability of the soil to keep the pH stable through the buffering effect of calcium carbonate, but this tactic is largely unusable in the case of wilderness lands.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] When calcium is leached from the needles of red spruce, these trees become less cold tolerant and exhibit winter injury and even death.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Acid rain may also affect crop productivity by necrosis or changes to soil nutrients, which ultimately prevent plants from reaching maturity.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Acid rain has a much less harmful effect on oceans on a global scale, but it creates an amplified impact in the shallower waters of coastal waters.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Acid rain can cause the ocean's pH to fall, known as ocean acidification, making it more difficult for different coastal species to create their exoskeletons that they need to survive and escape predation.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] These coastal species link together as part of the ocean's food chain, and without them being a source for other marine life to feed off of, more marine life will die.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Coral's limestone skeleton is particularly sensitive to pH decreases, because the calcium carbonate, a core component of the limestone skeleton, dissolves in acidic (low pH) solutions.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] In addition to acidification, excess nitrogen inputs from the atmosphere promote increased growth of phytoplankton and other marine plants, which, in turn, may cause more frequent harmful algal blooms and eutrophication (the creation of oxygen-depleted "dead zones") in some parts of the ocean.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] However, some studies on intertidal zones point to the prominence of acid rain as a cause of the observed decline in algal species richness.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Acid rain can negatively impact human health, especially when people breathe in particles released from acid rain.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The effects of acid rain on human health are complex and may be seen in several ways , such as respiratory issues for long-term exposure and indirect exposure through contaminated food and water sources.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Exposure to air pollutants associated with acid rain, such as nitrogen dioxide (NO2), may have a negative impact on respiratory health.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Water-soluble nitrogen dioxide accumulates in the tiny lung airways (bronchioles), where it is transformed into nitric and nitrous acids, causing damage to the cells of the respiratory tract by various mechanisms.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Pneumonia caused by nitric acids directly damages the epithelial cells lining the airways, resulting in pulmonary edema.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Exposure to nitrogen dioxide also reduces the immune response by inhibiting the generation of inflammatory cytokines by alveolar macrophages in response to bacterial infection, and more particularly in smokers.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The pollutant further reduces respiratory immunity by decreasing mucociliary clearance in the lower respiratory tract, which results in a reduced ability to remove respiratory infections.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The effects of sulfur trioxide and sulfuric acid are similar because the former produces sulfuric acid when it comes into touch with the wet surfaces of your skin or respiratory system.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The amount of SO3 breath through the mouth is larger than the amount of SO3 breath through the nose.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] When humans breathe in sulfur trioxide, small droplets of sulfuric acid will form inside the body and enter the respiratory tract to the lungs depending on the particle size.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The effects of SO3 on the respiratory system lead to breathing difficulty in people who have asthma symptoms.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Sulfur trioxide also causes very corrosive and irritation on the skin, eye, and gastrointestinal tracts when there is direct exposure to a specific concentration or long-term exposure.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Consuming concentrated sulfuric acid has been known to burn the mouth and throat, erode a hole in the stomach, burns when it comes into contact with skin, make your eyes weep if it gets into them, and mortality.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] A 25 parts per million (ppm) maximum for nitric oxide in working air has been set by the Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) for an 8-hour workday and a 40-hour workweek.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Additionally, OSHA has established a 5-ppm nitrogen dioxide exposure limit for 15 minutes in the workplace.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The not-to-exceed limits in the air, water, soil, or food that are recommended by regulations are often based on levels that affect animals before being modified to assist in safeguarding people.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Depending on whether they employ different animal studies, have different exposure lengths (e.g., an 8-hour workday versus a 24-hour day), or for other reasons, these not-to-exceed values can vary between federal bodies.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The amount of sulfur dioxide that can be emitted into the atmosphere is capped by the EPA.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] This reduces the quantity of sulfur dioxide in the air that turns into sulfur trioxide and sulfuric acid.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Sulfuric acid concentrations in workroom air are restricted by OSHA to 1 mg/m3.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Moreover, NIOSH advises a time-weighted average limit of 1 mg/m3.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Acid rain can damage buildings, historic monuments, and statues, especially those made of rocks, such as limestone and marble, that contain large amounts of calcium carbonate.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Acids in the rain react with the calcium compounds in the stones to create gypsum, which then flakes off.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The effects of this are commonly seen on old gravestones, where acid rain can cause the inscriptions to become completely illegible.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Acid rain also increases the corrosion rate of metals, in particular iron, steel, copper and bronze.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Places significantly impacted by acid rain around the globe include most of eastern Europe from Poland northward into Scandinavia, the eastern third of the United States, and southeastern Canada.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Other affected areas include the southeastern coast of China and Taiwan.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Many coal-firing power stations use flue-gas desulfurization (FGD) to remove sulfur-containing gases from their stack gases.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] For a typical coal-fired power station, FGD will remove 95% or more of the SO2 in the flue gases.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] An example of FGD is the wet scrubber which is commonly used.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] A wet scrubber is basically a reaction tower equipped with a fan that extracts hot smoke stack gases from a power plant into the tower.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Lime or limestone in slurry form is also injected into the tower to mix with the stack gases and combine with the sulfur dioxide present.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The calcium carbonate of the limestone produces pH-neutral calcium sulfate that is physically removed from the scrubber.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] That is, the scrubber turns sulfur pollution into industrial sulfates.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] In some areas the sulfates are sold to chemical companies as gypsum when the purity of calcium sulfate is high.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The effects of acid rain can last for generations, as the effects of pH level change can stimulate the continued leaching of undesirable chemicals into otherwise pristine water sources, killing off vulnerable insect and fish species and blocking efforts to restore native life.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Fluidized bed combustion also reduces the amount of sulfur emitted by power production.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Vehicle emissions control reduces emissions of nitrogen oxides from motor vehicles.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] International treaties on the long-range transport of atmospheric pollutants have been agreed upon by western countries for some time now.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Beginning in 1979, European countries convened in order to ratify general principles discussed during the UNECE Convention.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The purpose was to combat Long-Range Transboundary Air Pollution.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The 1985 Helsinki Protocol on the Reduction of Sulfur Emissions under the Convention on Long-Range Transboundary Air Pollution furthered the results of the convention.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Results of the treaty have already come to fruition, as evidenced by an approximate 40 percent drop in particulate matter in North America.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The effectiveness of the Convention in combatting acid rain has inspired further acts of international commitment to prevent the proliferation of particulate matter.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Canada and the US signed the Air Quality Agreement in 1991.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Most European countries and Canada signed the treaties.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Activity of the Long-Range Transboundary Air Pollution Convention remained dormant after 1999, when 27 countries convened to further reduce the effects of acid rain.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] In 2000, foreign cooperation to prevent acid rain was sparked in Asia for the first time.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Ten diplomats from countries ranging throughout the continent convened to discuss ways to prevent acid rain.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Following these discussions, the Acid Deposition Monitoring Network in East Asia (EANET) was established in 2001 as an intergovernmental initiative to provide science-based inputs for decision makers and promote international cooperation on acid deposition in East Asia.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] In 2023, the EANET member countries include Cambodia, China, Indonesia, Japan, Lao PDR, Malaysia, Mongolia, Myanmar, the Philippines, Republic of Korea, Russia, Thailand and Vietnam.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] In this regulatory scheme, every current polluting facility is given or may purchase on an open market an emissions allowance for each unit of a designated pollutant it emits.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] Operators can then install pollution control equipment, and sell portions of their emissions allowances they no longer need for their own operations, thereby recovering some of the capital cost of their investment in such equipment.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The intention is to give operators economic incentives to install pollution controls.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The first emissions trading market was established in the United States by enactment of the Clean Air Act Amendments of 1990.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] The overall goal of the Acid Rain Program established by the Act is to achieve significant environmental and public health benefits through reductions in emissions of sulfur dioxide (SO2) and nitrogen oxides (NOx), the primary causes of acid rain.
[src:habitat-destruction/acid-rain] To achieve this goal at the lowest cost to society, the program employs both regulatory and market based approaches for controlling air pollution.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-expansion] It is foreseen that most of the world's non-agrarian ecosystems (terrestrial and aquatic) will be affected adversely, from habitat loss, land degradation, overexploitation, and other problems.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-expansion] The intensified food (and biofuel) production will in particular affect the tropical regions.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-expansion] Most modern agriculture relies on intensive methods.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-expansion] Further expansion of the predominant farming types that rest on a small number of highly productive crops has led to a significant loss of biodiversity on a global scale already.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-expansion] Moreover, agricultural expansion continues to be the main driver of deforestation and forest fragmentation.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-expansion] Large-scale commercial agriculture (primarily cattle ranching and cultivation of soya bean and oil palm) accounted for 40 percent of tropical deforestation between 2000 and 2010, and local subsistence agriculture for another 33 percent.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-expansion] In the light of the already occurring and potential massive ecological effects, the need for sustainable practices is more urgent than ever.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-expansion] The FAO predicts that global arable land use will continue to grow from a 1.58 billion hectares (3.9×109 acres) in 2014 to 1.66 billion hectares (4.1×109 acres) in 2050, with most of this growth projected to result from developing countries.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-expansion] At the same time, arable land use in developed countries is likely to continue its decline.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-expansion] A well-known example of already ongoing agricultural expansion is the proliferation of palm oil production areas or the land conversion/deforestation for soy bean production in South America.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-expansion] Today's land grabbing activities are often a consequence of the strive for agricultural land by growing economies.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-expansion] In the beginning of the 21st century the palm oil industry caused a massive deforestation in Borneo with heavy consequences.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Management practices, or ignorance of them, play a crucial role in the amount and impact of these pollutants.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Management techniques range from animal management and housing to the spread of pesticides and fertilizers in global agricultural practices, which can have major environmental impacts.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Bad management practices include poorly managed animal feeding operations, overgrazing, plowing, fertilizer, and improper, excessive, or badly timed use of pesticides.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Pollutants from agriculture greatly affect water quality and can be found in lakes, rivers, wetlands, estuaries, and groundwater.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Pollutants from farming include sediments, nutrients, pathogens, pesticides, metals, and salts.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Animal agriculture has an outsized impact on pollutants that enter the environment.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Bacteria and pathogens in manure can make their way into streams and groundwater if grazing, storing manure in lagoons and applying manure to fields is not properly managed.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Air pollution caused by agriculture through land use changes and animal agriculture practices have an outsized impact on climate change.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Addressing these concerns was a central part of the IPCC Special Report on Climate Change and Land as well as in the 2024 UNEP Actions on Air Quality report.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Mitigation of agricultural pollution is a key component in the development of a sustainable food system.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] It has been conceded that in the absence of pest control measures, crop losses before harvesting would typically amount to 40 percent.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Pesticide persistence is nonetheless a major issue.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] For example 2,4-D and atrazine have with lifetimes up to 20 years.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] DDT, aldrin, dieldrin, endrin, heptachlor, and toxaphene are also long-lived.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] The persistence of pesticides and herbicides persist depends on the compound's unique chemistry.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Pesticides can also accumulate in animals that eat contaminated pests and soil organisms.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] The primary danger associated with pesticide application lies in its impact on non-target organisms.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] In principle, biopesticides, derived from natural sources, could reduce overall agricultural pollution.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Furthermore, biopesticides often suffer the same negative impacts as synthetic pesticides.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] In the United States, biopesticides are subject to fewer environmental regulations.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Many biopesticides are permitted under the National Organic Program, United States Department of Agriculture, standards for organic crop production.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Pesticide leaching occurs when aqueous solutions of pesticides migrate to off-target sites.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Leaching is a major source of groundwater pollution.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Leaching is affected by the soil, the pesticide, and rainfall and irrigation.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Leaching is more problematic with water-soluble pesticides and when the soil tends to be sandy in texture; if excessive watering occurs just after pesticide application; if the adsorption ability of the pesticide to the soil is low.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] In addition to treated fields, Leaching may also originate from pesticide mixing areas, pesticide application machinery washing sites, or disposal areas.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] While providing crops with nutrients to increase crop yields, fertilizers can pose risks to human and ecological health.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Most common nitrogen sources are NO3− (nitrate) and NH4+ (ammonium).
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Although leading to increased crop yield, nitrogen fertilizers can also negatively affect groundwater and surface waters, pollute the atmosphere, and degrade soil health.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Not all nutrient applied through fertilizer are taken up by the crops, and the remainder accumulates in the soil or is lost as runoff.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Nitrate fertilizers are much more likely to be lost to the soil profile through runoff because of its high solubility and like charges between the molecule and negatively charged clay particles.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] High application rates of nitrogen-containing fertilizers combined with the high water-solubility of nitrate leads to increased runoff into surface water as well as leaching into groundwater, thereby causing groundwater pollution.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Nitrate levels above 10 mg/L (10 ppm) in groundwater can cause "blue baby syndrome" (acquired methemoglobinemia) in infants and possibly thyroid disease and various types of cancer.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] They allow nitrogen to flow between the atmosphere, which is around 78% nitrogen) and the biosphere.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Other significant processes in the nitrogen cycle are nitrification and ammonification which convert ammonium to nitrate or nitrite and organic matter to ammonia respectively.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Because these processes keep nitrogen concentrations relatively stable in most ecosystems, a large influx of nitrogen from agricultural runoff can cause serious disruption.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] A common result of this in aquatic ecosystems is eutrophication, which in turn creates hypoxic and anoxic conditions – both of which are deadly and/or damaging to many species..
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Beyond eutrophication, nitrogen pollution—specifically in the form of nitrite (NO2−)—acts as a significant driver of species turnover in riverine ecosystems.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Research indicates that aquatic invertebrates exhibit a wide range of sensitivities; while molluscs are relatively tolerant, aquatic insects such as mayflies and stoneflies are highly sensitive to nitrite exposure.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] In groups like amphipods, sensitivity varies by habitat, with upstream species (e.g., *Gammarus fossarum*) being more vulnerable than midstream or invasive downstream species (e.g., *Gammarus roeselii*).
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] This differential sensitivity can lead to the replacement of native sensitive taxa with more tolerant ones, potentially altering ecosystem functions like leaf litter decomposition and nutrient cycling.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Nitrogen fertilization can also release NH3 gases into the atmosphere which can then be converted into NOx compounds.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] A greater amount of NOx compounds in the atmosphere can result in the acidification of aquatic ecosystems and cause various respiratory issues in humans.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Fertilization can also release N2O which is a greenhouse gas and can facilitate the destruction of ozone (O3) in the stratosphere.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Soils that receive nitrogen fertilizers can also be damaged.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] An increase in plant available nitrogen will increase a crop's net primary production, and eventually, soil microbial activity will increase as a result of the larger inputs of nitrogen from fertilizers and carbon compounds through decomposed biomass.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Excess nitrogen can disrupt mutualisms; for example, in the legumes-rhizobia resource mutualism nitrogen deposition results in the evolution of less-cooperative rhizobia.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Because of the increase in decomposition in the soil, its organic matter content will be depleted which results in lower overall soil health.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] The most common form of phosphorus fertilizer is phosphate (PO43-).
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] It is applied as synthetic phosphate salts as well as manure and compost.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Most agricultural crops only require a small amount of phosphorus, as such, the amount of phosphorus supplied is often excessive.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Excess phosphorus typically enters surface waters.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Phosphorus is largest contributor to eutrophication, especially in freshwaters.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] In addition to depleting oxygen levels in surface waters, algae and cyanobacteria blooms can produce cyanotoxins which are harmful to human and animal health as well as many aquatic organisms.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Cadmium is common in phosphorus-containing fertilizers varies considerably and can be problematic.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] The phosphate rock used in their manufacture can contain as much as 188 mg/kg cadmium (examples are deposits on Nauru and the Christmas islands).
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Continuous use of high-cadmium fertilizer can contaminate soil and plants.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Limits to the cadmium content of phosphate fertilizers has been considered by the European Commission.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Producers of phosphorus-containing fertilizers now select phosphate rock based on the cadmium content.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Phosphate rocks can also contain high levels of fluoride.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Consequently, the widespread use of phosphate fertilizers has increased soil fluoride concentrations.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] It has been found that food contamination from fertilizer is of little concern as plants accumulate little fluoride from the soil; of greater concern is the possibility of fluoride toxicity to livestock that ingest contaminated soils.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Also of possible concern are the effects of fluoride on soil microorganisms.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Farm machinery and equipment emitting substantial quantities of harmful gases, and operation of the machinery can result in other chemical contamination, such as oil spills, hydraulic fluid leakage, and tire particulates.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Other equipment and materials used in agriculture can introduce pollutants into the soil, and subsequently the environment.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] For example, the widespread use of plastic sheeting for greenhouses, plastic storage for applications like animal feed and seed bags and sillage, and plastic mulch means that both microplastic and macroplastic are increasingly introduced into farmed landscapes.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] A 2021 study by FAO of plastic waste in agriculture, found an estimated 10 million tons of plastic waste produced each year.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Collection of agricultural plastics is very low globally, with much of never getting collected.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Agriculture contributes greatly to soil erosion and sediment deposition through intensive management or inefficient land cover.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] It is estimated that agricultural land degradation is leading to an irreversible decline in fertility on about 6 million ha of fertile land each year.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] The accumulation of sediments (i.e. sedimentation) in runoff water affects water quality in various ways.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Sedimentation can decrease the transport capacity of ditches, streams, rivers, and navigation channels.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] It can also limit the amount of light penetrating the water, which affects aquatic biota.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] The resulting turbidity from sedimentation can interfere with feeding habits of fishes, affecting population dynamics.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Sedimentation also affects the transport and accumulation of pollutants, including phosphorus and various pesticides.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Natural soil biogeochemical processes result in the emission of various greenhouse gases, including nitrous oxide.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Agricultural management practices can affect emission levels.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] For example, tillage levels have also been shown to affect nitrous oxide emissions.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] From an environmental perspective, fertilizing, overproduction and the use of pesticides in conventional farming has caused, and is causing, enormous damage worldwide to local ecosystems, soil health, biodiversity, groundwater and drinking water supplies, and sometimes farmers' health and fertility.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Organic farming typically reduces some environmental impact relative to conventional farming, but the scale of reduction can be difficult to quantify and varies depending on farming methods.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] In some cases, reducing food waste and dietary changes might provide greater benefits.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] A 2020 study at the Technical University of Munich found that the greenhouse gas emissions of organically farmed plant-based food were lower than conventionally farmed plant-based food.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] The greenhouse gas costs of organically produced meat were approximately the same as non-organically produced meat.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] However, the same paper noted that a shift from conventional to organic practices would likely be beneficial for long-term efficiency and ecosystem services, and probably improve soil over time.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Recent research has suggested that the usage of organic fertilizers and cover crops can enhance soil organic carbon, nutrient cycling, and biodiversity.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Simultaneously, it could also reduce greenhouse gas emissions when it is managed effectively.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Conservation agriculture relies on principles of minimal soil disturbance, the use of mulch and/or cover crops as soil cover, and crop species diversification.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] It enables the reduction of fertilizers, which in turn reduces ammonia emissions and greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] It also stabilizes soil, which slows down the release of carbon into the atmosphere.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Manures and biosolids, although having value as fertilizers, they may also contain contaminants, including pharmaceuticals and personal care products (PPCPs).
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] A wide variety and vast quantity of PPCPs consumed by animals.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] The United Nations Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) predicted that 18% of anthropogenic greenhouse gases come directly or indirectly from the world's livestock.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] This report also suggested that the emissions from livestock were greater than that of the transportation sector.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] While livestock do currently play a role in producing greenhouse gas emissions, the estimates have been argued to be a misrepresentation.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] While the FAO used a life-cycle assessment of animal agriculture (i.e. all aspects including emissions from growing crops for feed, transportation to slaughter, etc.), they did not apply the same assessment for the transportation sector.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Alternate sources claim that FAO estimates are too low, stating that the global livestock industry could be responsible for up to 51% of emitted atmospheric greenhouse gasses rather than 18%.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Critics say the difference in estimates come from the FAO's use of outdated data.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Regardless, if the FAO's report of 18% is accurate, that still makes livestock the second-largest greenhouse-gas-polluter.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] A PNAS model showed that even if animals were completely removed from U.S. agriculture and diets, U.S.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] GHG emissions would be decreased by 2.6% only (or 28% of agricultural GHG emissions).
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] This is because of the need to replace animal manures by fertilizers and to replace also other animal coproducts, and because livestock now use human-inedible food and fiber processing byproducts.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Moreover, people would suffer from a greater number of deficiencies in essential nutrients although they would get a greater excess of energy, possibly leading to greater obesity.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] The increasing globalization of agriculture has resulted in the accidental transport of pests, weeds, and diseases to novel ranges.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] If they establish, they become an invasive species that can impact populations of native species and threaten agricultural production.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] For example, the transport of bumblebees reared in Europe and shipped to the United States and/or Canada for use as commercial pollinators has led to the introduction of an Old World parasite to the New World.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] This introduction may play a role in recent native bumble bee declines in North America.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Agriculturally introduced species can also hybridize with native species resulting in a decline in genetic biodiversity and threaten agricultural production.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Habitat disturbance associated with farming practices themselves can also facilitate the establishment of these introduced organisms.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Contaminated machinery, livestock and fodder, and contaminated crop or pasture seed can also lead to the spread of weeds.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Quarantines (see biosecurity) are one way in which prevention of the spread of invasive species can be regulated at the policy level.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] A quarantine is a legal instrument that restricts the movement of infested material from areas where an invasive species is present to areas in which it is absent.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] The World Trade Organization has international regulations concerning the quarantine of pests and diseases under the Agreement on the Application of Sanitary and Phytosanitary Measures.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Individual countries often have their own quarantine regulations.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] In the United States, for example, the United States Department of Agriculture/Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service (USDA/APHIS) administers domestic (within the United States) and foreign (importations from outside the United States) quarantines.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] These quarantines are enforced by inspectors at state borders and ports of entry.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] The use of biological pest control agents, or using predators, parasitoids, parasites, and pathogens to control agricultural pests, has the potential to reduce agricultural pollution associated with other pest control techniques, such as pesticide use.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] The merits of introducing non-native biocontrol agents have been widely debated, however.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Once released, the introduction of a biocontrol agent can be irreversible.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Potential ecological issues could include the dispersal from agricultural habitats into natural environments, and host-switching or adapting to utilize a native species.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] In addition, predicting the interaction outcomes in complex ecosystems and potential ecological impacts prior to release can be difficult.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] One example of a biocontrol program that resulted in ecological damage occurred in North America, where a parasitoid of butterflies was introduced to control gypsy moth and browntail moth.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] This parasitoid is capable of utilizing many butterfly host species, and likely resulted in the decline and extirpation of several native silk moth species.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] In order to prevent agricultural pollution, quarantine and extensive research on the organism's potential efficacy and ecological impacts are required prior to introduction.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] If approved, attempts are made to colonize and disperse the biocontrol agent in appropriate agricultural settings.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Continual evaluations on their efficacy are conducted.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] GMO crops can, however, result in genetic contamination of native plant species through hybridization.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] This could lead to increased weediness of the plant or the extinction of the native species.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] In addition, the transgenic plant itself may become a weed if the modification improves its fitness in a given environment.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] There are also concerns that non-target organisms, such as pollinators and natural enemies, could be poisoned by accidental ingestion of Bt-producing plants.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] A recent study testing the effects of Bt corn pollen dusting nearby milkweed plants on larval feeding of the monarch butterfly found that the threat to populations of the monarch was low.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] The use of GMO crop plants engineered for herbicide resistance can also indirectly increase the amount of agricultural pollution associated with herbicide use.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] For example, the increased use of herbicide in herbicide-resistant corn fields in the mid-western United States is decreasing the amount of milkweeds available for monarch butterfly larvae.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Regulation of the release of genetic modified organisms vary based on the type of organism and the country concerned.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] While there may be some concerns regarding the use of GM products, it may also be the solution to some of the existing animal agriculture pollution issues.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] One of the main sources of pollution, particularly vitamin and mineral drift in soils, comes from a lack of digestive efficiency in animals.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] By improving digestive efficiency, it is possible to minimize both the cost of animal production and the environmental damage.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] One successful example of this technology and its potential application is the Enviropig.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] The Enviropig is a genetically modified Yorkshire pig that expresses phytase in its saliva.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Grains, such as corn and wheat, have phosphorus that is bound in a naturally indigestible form known as phytic acid.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Phosphorus, an essential nutrient for pigs, is then added to the diet, since it can not be broken down in the pigs digestive tract.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] As a result, nearly all of the phosphorus naturally found in the grain is wasted in the feces, and can contribute to elevated levels in the soil.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Phytase is an enzyme that is able to break down the otherwise indigestible phytic acid, making it available to the pig.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] The ability of the Enviropig to digest the phosphorus from the grains eliminates the waste of that natural phosphorus (20-60% reduction), while also eliminating the need to supplement the nutrient in feed.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] One of the main contributors to air, soil and water pollution is animal waste.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] According to a 2005 report by the USDA, more than 335–million tons of "dry matter" waste (the waste after water is removed) is produced annually on farms in the United States.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Animal feeding operations produce about 100 times more manure than the amount of human sewage sludge processed in US municipal waste water plants each year.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Diffuse source pollution from agricultural fertilizers is more difficult to trace, monitor and control.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] High nitrate concentrations are found in groundwater and may reach 50 mg/litre (the EU Directive limit).
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] In ditches and river courses, nutrient pollution from fertilizers causes eutrophication.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] This is worse in winter, after autumn ploughing has released a surge of nitrates; winter rainfall is heavier increasing runoff and leaching, and there is lower plant uptake.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] EPA suggests that one dairy farm with 2,500 cows produces as much waste as a city with around 411,000 residents.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] The US National Research Council has identified odors as the most significant animal emission problem at the local level.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Different animal systems have adopted several waste management procedures to deal with the large amount of waste produced annually.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] The advantages of manure treatment are a reduction in the amount of manure that needs to be transported and applied to crops, as well as reduced soil compaction.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Nutrients are reduced as well, meaning that less cropland is needed for manure to be spread upon.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Manure treatment can also reduce the risk of human health and biosecurity risks by reducing the amount of pathogens present in manure.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Undiluted animal manure or slurry is one hundred times more concentrated than domestic sewage, and can carry an intestinal parasite, *Cryptosporidium,* which is difficult to detect but can be passed to humans.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Silage liquor (from fermented wet grass) is even stronger than slurry, with a low pH and very high biological oxygen demand.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] With a low pH, silage liquor can be highly corrosive; it can attack synthetic materials, causing damage to storage equipment, and leading to accidental spillage.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] All of these advantages can be optimized by using the right manure management system on the right farm based on the resources that are available.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Composting is a solid manure management system that relies on solid manure from bedded pack pens, or the solids from a liquid manure separator.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] There are two methods of composting, active and passive.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Manure is churned periodically during active composting, whereas in passive composting it is not.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Passive composting has been found to have lower green house gas emissions due to incomplete decomposition and lower gas diffusion rates.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Manure can be mechanically separated into a solid and liquid portion for easier management.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Liquids (4–8% dry matter) can be used easily in pump systems for convenient spread over crops and the solid fraction (15–30% dry matter) can be used as stall bedding, spread on crops, composted or exported.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Anaerobic digestion is the biological treatment of liquid animal waste using bacteria in an area absent of air, which promotes the decomposition of organic solids.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Hot water is used to heat the waste in order to increase the rate of biogas production.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] The remaining liquid is nutrient rich and can be used on fields as a fertilizer and methane gas that can be burned directly on the biogas stove or in an engine generator to produce electricity and heat.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Methane is about 20 times more potent as a greenhouse gas than carbon dioxide, which has significant negative environmental effects if not controlled properly.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Anaerobic treatment of waste is the best method for controlling the odor associated with manure management.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Biological treatment lagoons also use anaerobic digestion to break down solids, but at a much slower rate.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Lagoons are kept at ambient temperatures as opposed to the heated digestion tanks.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Lagoons require large land areas and high dilution volumes to work properly, so they do not work well in many climates in the northern United States.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Lagoons also offer the benefit of reduced odor and biogas is made available for heat and electric power.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] Studies have demonstrated that GHG emissions are reduced using aerobic digestion systems.
[src:habitat-destruction/agricultural-runoff] GHG emission reductions and credits can help compensate for the higher installation cost of cleaner aerobic technologies and facilitate producer adoption of environmentally superior technologies to replace current anaerobic lagoons.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] As of 2021, small farms, of which the vast majority are one hectare (about 2.5 acres) or smaller, produce about one-third of the world's food.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Moreover, five of every six farms in the world consist of fewer than 2 hectares (4.9 acres) and take up only around 12% of all agricultural land.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] In terms of total land use, large farms are dominant.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] While only 1% of all farms globally are greater than 50 hectares (120 acres), they encompass more than 70% of the world's farmland.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Further, nearly 40% of all global agricultural land is found on farms larger than 1,000 hectares (2,500 acres).
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Farms and farming greatly influence rural economics and greatly shape rural society, affecting both the direct agricultural workforce and broader businesses that support the farms and farming populations.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] The major agricultural products can be broadly grouped into foods, fibers, fuels, and raw materials (such as rubber and timber).
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Food classes include cereals (grains), vegetables, fruits, cooking oils, meat, milk, eggs, and fungi.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Global agricultural production amounts to approximately 11 billion tonnes of food, 32 million tonnes of natural fibers and 4 billion m3 of wood.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] However, around 14% of the world's food is lost from production before reaching the retail level.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Modern agronomy, plant breeding, agrochemicals such as pesticides and fertilizers, and technological developments have sharply increased crop yields, but also contributed to ecological and environmental damage.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Selective breeding and modern practices in animal husbandry have similarly increased the output of meat, but have raised concerns about animal welfare and environmental damage.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Environmental issues include contributions to climate change, depletion of aquifers, deforestation, antibiotic resistance, and other agricultural pollution.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Agriculture is both a cause of and sensitive to environmental degradation, such as biodiversity loss, desertification, soil degradation, and climate change, all of which can cause decreases in crop yield.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Genetically modified organisms are widely used, although some countries ban them.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] The word *agriculture* is a late Middle English adaptation of Latin *agricultūra*, from *ager* 'field' and *cultūra* 'cultivation' or 'growing'.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Agriculture is defined with varying scopes, in its broadest sense using natural resources to "produce commodities which maintain life, including food, fiber, forest products, horticultural crops, and their related services".
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Thus defined, it includes arable farming, horticulture, animal husbandry and forestry, but horticulture and forestry are in practice often excluded.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] It may also be broadly decomposed into **plant agriculture**, which concerns the cultivation of useful plants, and **animal agriculture**, the production of agricultural animals.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] While agriculture usually refers to human activities, other species have been cultivating crops for up to 60 million years, such as some ant (see agriculture in ants), termite and beetle.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] The development of agriculture enabled the human population to grow many times larger than could be sustained by hunting and gathering.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Agriculture began independently in different parts of the globe, and included a diverse range of taxa, in at least 11 separate centers of origin.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Wild grains were collected and eaten from at least 105,000 years ago.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] In the Paleolithic Levant, 23,000 years ago, cereals cultivation of emmer, barley, and oats has been observed near the sea of Galilee.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Rice was domesticated in China between 11,500 and 6200 BC with the earliest known cultivation from 5700 BC, followed by mung, soy and azuki beans.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Sheep were domesticated in Mesopotamia between 13,000 and 11,000 years ago.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Cattle were domesticated from the wild aurochs in the areas of modern Turkey and Pakistan some 10,500 years ago.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Pig production emerged in Eurasia, including Europe, East Asia and Southwest Asia, where wild boar were first domesticated about 10,500 years ago.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] In the Andes of South America, the potato was domesticated between 10,000 and 7,000 years ago, along with beans, coca, llamas, alpacas, and guinea pigs.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Sugarcane and some root vegetables were domesticated in New Guinea around 9,000 years ago.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Sorghum was domesticated in the Sahel region of Africa by 7,000 years ago.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Cotton was domesticated in Peru by 5,600 years ago, and was independently domesticated in Eurasia.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] In Mesoamerica, wild teosinte was bred into maize (corn) from 10,000 to 6,000 years ago.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] The horse was domesticated in the Eurasian Steppes around 3500 BC.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Scholars have offered multiple hypotheses to explain the historical origins of agriculture.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Studies of the transition from hunter-gatherer to agricultural societies indicate an initial period of intensification and increasing sedentism; examples are the Natufian culture in the Levant, and the Early Chinese Neolithic in China.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Then, wild stands that had previously been harvested started to be planted, and gradually came to be domesticated.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] In Eurasia, the Sumerians started to live in villages from about 8000 BC, relying on the Tigris and Euphrates rivers and a canal system for irrigation.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Ploughs appear in pictographs around 3000 BC; seed-ploughs around 2300 BC.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Farmers grew wheat, barley, vegetables such as lentils and onions, and fruits including dates, grapes, and figs.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Ancient Egyptian agriculture relied on the Nile River and its seasonal flooding.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Farming started in the predynastic period at the end of the Paleolithic, after 10,000 BC.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Staple food crops were grains such as wheat and barley, alongside industrial crops such as flax and papyrus.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] In India, wheat, barley and jujube were domesticated by 9000 BC, soon followed by sheep and goats.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Cattle, sheep and goats were domesticated in Mehrgarh culture by 8000–6000 BC.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Cotton was cultivated by the 5th–4th millennium BC.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Archeological evidence indicates an animal-drawn plough from 2500 BC in the Indus Valley civilization.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] In China, from the 5th century BC, there was a nationwide granary system and widespread silk farming.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Water-powered grain mills were in use by the 1st century BC, followed by irrigation.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] By the late 2nd century, heavy ploughs had been developed with iron ploughshares and mouldboards.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Asian rice was domesticated 8,200–13,500 years ago – depending on the molecular clock estimate that is used– on the Pearl River in southern China with a single genetic origin from the wild rice *Oryza rufipogon*.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] In Greece and Rome, the major cereals were wheat, emmer, and barley, alongside vegetables including peas, beans, and olives.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Sheep and goats were kept mainly for dairy products.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] In the Americas, crops domesticated in Mesoamerica (apart from teosinte) include squash, beans, and cacao.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Cocoa was domesticated by the Mayo Chinchipe of the upper Amazon around 3000 BC.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] The turkey was probably domesticated in Mexico or the American Southwest.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] The Aztecs developed irrigation systems, formed terraced hillsides, fertilized their soil, and developed chinampas or artificial islands.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] The Mayas used extensive canal and raised field systems to farm swampland from 400 BC.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] In South America agriculture may have begun about 9000 BC with the domestication of squash (Cucurbita) and other plants.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Coca was domesticated in the Andes, as were the peanut, tomato, tobacco, and pineapple.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Cotton was domesticated in Peru by 3600 BC.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Animals including llamas, alpacas, and guinea pigs were domesticated there.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] In North America, the indigenous people of the East domesticated crops such as sunflower, tobacco, squash and *Chenopodium*.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Wild foods including wild rice and maple sugar were harvested.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] The domesticated strawberry is a hybrid of a Chilean and a North American species, developed by breeding in Europe and North America.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] The indigenous people of the Southwest and the Pacific Northwest practiced forest gardening and fire-stick farming.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] The natives controlled fire on a regional scale to create a low-intensity fire ecology that sustained a low-density agriculture in loose rotation; a sort of "wild" permaculture.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] A system of companion planting called the Three Sisters was developed in North America.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] The three crops were winter squash, maize, and climbing beans.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Indigenous Australians, long supposed to have been nomadic hunter-gatherers, practiced systematic burning, possibly to enhance natural productivity in fire-stick farming.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Scholars have pointed out that hunter-gatherers need a productive environment to support gathering without cultivation.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Because the forests of New Guinea have few food plants, early humans may have used "selective burning" to increase the productivity of the wild karuka fruit trees to support the hunter-gatherer way of life.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] The Gunditjmara and other groups developed eel farming and fish trapping systems from some 5,000 years ago.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] There is evidence of 'intensification' across the whole continent over that period.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] In two regions of Australia, the central west coast and eastern central, early farmers cultivated yams, native millet, and bush onions, possibly in permanent settlements.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] In the Middle Ages, compared to the Roman period, agriculture in Western Europe became more focused on self-sufficiency.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] The agricultural population under feudalism was typically organized into manors consisting of several hundred or more acres of land presided over by a lord of the manor with a Roman Catholic church and priest.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Thanks to the exchange with the Al-Andalus where the Arab Agricultural Revolution was underway, European agriculture transformed, with improved techniques and the diffusion of crop plants, including the introduction of sugar, rice, cotton and fruit trees (such as the orange).
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] After 1492, the Columbian exchange brought New World crops such as maize, potatoes, tomatoes, sweet potatoes, and manioc to Europe, and Old World crops such as wheat, barley, rice, and turnips, and livestock (including horses, cattle, sheep and goats) to the Americas.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Irrigation, crop rotation, and fertilizers advanced from the 17th century with the British Agricultural Revolution, allowing global population to rise significantly.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Since 1900, agriculture in developed nations, and to a lesser extent in the developing world, has seen large rises in productivity as mechanization replaces human labor, and assisted by synthetic fertilizers, pesticides, and selective breeding.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] The Haber-Bosch method allowed the synthesis of ammonium nitrate fertilizer on an industrial scale, greatly increasing crop yields and sustaining a further increase in global population.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Pastoralism involves managing domesticated animals.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] In nomadic pastoralism, herds of livestock are moved from place to place in search of pasture, fodder, and water.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] This type of farming is practiced in arid and semi-arid regions of Sahara, Central Asia and some parts of India.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] In shifting cultivation, a small area of forest is cleared by cutting and burning the trees.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] The cleared land is used for growing crops for a few years until the soil becomes too infertile, and the area is abandoned.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Another patch of land is selected and the process is repeated.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] This type of farming is practiced mainly in areas with abundant rainfall where the forest regenerates quickly.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] This practice is used in Northeast India, Southeast Asia, and the Amazon Basin.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Subsistence farming is practiced to satisfy family or local needs alone, with little left over for transport elsewhere.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] It is intensively practiced in Monsoon Asia and South-East Asia.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] An estimated 2.5 billion subsistence farmers worked in 2018, cultivating about 60% of the earth's arable land.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Intensive farming is cultivation to maximize productivity, with a low fallow ratio and a high use of inputs (water, fertilizer, pesticide and automation).
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] It is practiced mainly in developed countries.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] From the twentieth century onwards, intensive agriculture increased crop productivity.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] It substituted synthetic fertilizers and pesticides for labor, but caused increased water pollution, and often involved farm subsidies.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Soil degradation and diseases such as stem rust are major concerns globally; approximately 40% of the world's agricultural land is seriously degraded.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Modern agriculture has raised or encountered ecological, political, and economic issues including water pollution, biofuels, genetically modified organisms, tariffs and farm subsidies, leading to alternative approaches such as the organic movement.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Unsustainable farming practices in North America led to the Dust Bowl of the 1930s.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] In recent years there has been a backlash against the environmental effects of conventional agriculture, resulting in the organic, regenerative, and sustainable agriculture movements.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] One of the major forces behind this movement has been the European Union, which first certified organic food in 1991 and began reform of its Common Agricultural Policy (CAP) in 2005 to phase out commodity-linked farm subsidies, also known as decoupling.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] The growth of organic farming has renewed research in alternative technologies such as integrated pest management, selective breeding, and controlled-environment agriculture.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] There are concerns about the lower yield associated with organic farming and its impact on global food security.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Recent mainstream technological developments include genetically modified food.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] During the 60-year period between 1964 and 2023, most of the increase in agricultural production was achieved through intensification, while the expansion of agricultural land was limited to just 8%.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] In the twenty-first century, between 2001 and 2023, global agricultural area decreased by 78 million hectares (Mha) (−2%), with cropland area increasing by 78 Mha and permanent meadows and pastures decreasing by 151 Mha.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] These changes exhibit significant regional variations.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Sub-Saharan Africa witnessed cropland expansion of 69 Mha accompanied by 72 Mha of forest loss, while Latin America saw 25 Mha of cropland growth alongside 85 Mha of net forest area loss.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Agricultural expansion remains the primary driver of global deforestation, accounting for nearly 90% of forest loss.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] In this century, another important aspect to consider is that approximately 3.6 Mha of croplands are abandoned annually, with land degradation likely playing a significant role in these losses.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] By 2015, the agricultural output of China was the largest in the world, followed by the European Union, India and the United States.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Economists measure the total factor productivity of agriculture, according to which agriculture in the United States is roughly 1.7 times more productive than it was in 1948.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Agriculture employed 873 million people in 2021, or 27% of the global workforce, 916 million in 2023, compared with 1 027 million (or 40%) in 2000.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] The share of agriculture in global GDP was stable at around 4% since 2000–2023.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Despite increases in agricultural production and productivity, between 702 and 828 million people were affected by hunger in 2021.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Food insecurity and malnutrition can be the result of conflict, climate extremes and variability and economic swings.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] It can also be caused by a country's structural characteristics such as income status and natural resource endowments as well as its political economy.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Pesticide use in agriculture went up 62% between 2000 and 2021, with the Americas accounting for half the use in 2021.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] The International Fund for Agricultural Development posits that an increase in smallholder agriculture may be part of the solution to concerns about food prices and overall food security, given the favorable experience of Vietnam.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Agriculture provides about one-quarter of all global employment, more than half in sub-Saharan Africa and almost 60 percent in low-income countries.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] As countries develop, other jobs have historically pulled workers away from agriculture, and labor-saving innovations increase agricultural productivity by reducing labor requirements per unit of output.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Over time, a combination of labor supply and labor demand trends have driven down the share of population employed in agriculture.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] During the 16th century in Europe, between 55 and 75% of the population was engaged in agriculture; by the 19th century, this had dropped to between 35 and 65%.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] In the same countries today, the figure is less than 10%.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] At the start of the 21st century, some one billion people, or over 1/3 of the available work force, were employed in agriculture.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] This constitutes approximately 70% of the global employment of children, and in many countries constitutes the largest percentage of women of any industry.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] The service sector overtook the agricultural sector as the largest global employer in 2007.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] In many developed countries, immigrants help fill labor shortages in high-value agriculture activities that are difficult to mechanize.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Foreign farm workers from mostly Eastern Europe, North Africa and South Asia constituted around one-third of the salaried agricultural workforce in Spain, Italy, Greece and Portugal in 2013.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Around the world, women make up a large share of the population employed in agriculture.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] This share is growing in all developing regions except East and Southeast Asia where women already make up about 50 percent of the agricultural workforce.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Women make up 47 percent of the agricultural workforce in sub-Saharan Africa, a rate that has not changed significantly in the past few decades.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Women who work in agricultural production tend to do so under highly unfavorable conditions.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] They tend to be concentrated in the poorest countries, where alternative livelihoods are not available, and they maintain the intensity of their work in conditions of climate-induced weather shocks and in situations of conflict.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Women are less likely to participate as entrepreneurs and independent farmers and are engaged in the production of less lucrative crops.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] The gender gap in land productivity between female- and male managed farms of the same size is 24 percent.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] On average, women earn 18.4 percent less than men in wage employment in agriculture; this means that women receive 82 cents for every dollar earned by men.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Progress has been slow in closing gaps in women's access to irrigation and in ownership of livestock, too.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Women in agriculture still have significantly less access than men to inputs, including improved seeds, fertilizers and mechanized equipment.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] On a positive note, the gender gap in access to mobile internet in low- and middle-income countries fell from 25 percent to 16 percent between 2017 and 2021, and the gender gap in access to bank accounts narrowed from 9 to 6 percentage points.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Women are as likely as men to adopt new technologies when the necessary enabling factors are put in place and they have equal access to complementary resources.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Agriculture, specifically farming, remains a hazardous industry, and farmers worldwide remain at high risk of work-related injuries, lung disease, noise-induced hearing loss, skin diseases, as well as certain cancers related to chemical use and prolonged sun exposure.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] On industrialized farms, injuries frequently involve the use of agricultural machinery, and a common cause of fatal agricultural injuries in developed countries is tractor rollovers.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Pesticides and other chemicals used in farming can be hazardous to worker health, and workers exposed to pesticides may experience illness or have children with birth defects.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] As an industry in which families commonly share in work and live on the farm itself, entire families can be at risk for injuries, illness, and death.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Ages 0–6 may be an especially vulnerable population in agriculture; common causes of fatal injuries among young farm workers include drowning, machinery and motor accidents, including with all-terrain vehicles.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Occupational fatality data from the last decade indicate that, when looking at all industries, agriculture had the leading number of work-related deaths for youth.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Within this industry, youth between the ages of 10 and 15 suffered the most non-fatal work-related injuries.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] While farming is hazardous, studies have looked at the fact that there are also many benefits to growing up and living on a farm.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] The International Labor Organization considers agriculture "one of the most hazardous of all economic sectors".
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] It estimates that the annual work-related death toll among agricultural employees is at least 170,000, twice the average rate of other jobs.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] In addition, incidences of death, injury and illness related to agricultural activities often go unreported.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] The organization has developed the Safety and Health in Agriculture Convention, 2001, which covers the range of risks in the agriculture occupation, the prevention of these risks and the role that individuals and organizations engaged in agriculture should play.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] In the United States, agriculture has been identified by the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health as a priority industry sector in the National Occupational Research Agenda to identify and provide intervention strategies for occupational health and safety issues.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] In the European Union, the European Agency for Safety and Health at Work has issued guidelines on implementing health and safety directives in agriculture, livestock farming, horticulture, and forestry.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] The Agricultural Safety and Health Council of America (ASHCA) also holds a yearly summit to discuss safety.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Extending over 4.8 billion ha in 2025 – the equivalent of one-third of the Earth's land surface – agriculture has a greater impact on land and water resources compared with any other economic sector.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Pressure on land, soil and water resources has seriously compromised the performance and future prospects of agriculture, resulting in further loss of productive land and reduced water availability for farming and other forms of agricultural production.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Agricultural expansion drives deforestation and is one of the primary causes of the degradation of carbon-rich ecosystems such as peatlands.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] An estimated 64% of agricultural land is at risk of pesticide pollution, which damages biodiversity by destroying pollinators, harms soil microbiota and makes agrifood systems less resilient to pests, pathogens and climate change.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Accounting for 72% of global freshwater withdrawals, a figure predicted to rise further in the future, agriculture contributes to and is increasingly affected by water scarcity.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Overexploitation of groundwater and seawater intrusion in coastal aquifers is widespread, with major implications for food security.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Overall production varies by country as listed.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Cropping systems vary among farms depending on the available resources and constraints; geography and climate of the farm; government policy; economic, social and political pressures; and the philosophy and culture of the farmer.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Shifting cultivation (or slash and burn) is a system in which forests are burnt, releasing nutrients to support cultivation of annual and then perennial crops for a period of several years.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Then the plot is left fallow to regrow forest, and the farmer moves to a new plot, returning after many more years (10–20).
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] This fallow period is shortened if population density grows, requiring the input of nutrients (fertilizer or manure) and some manual pest control.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Annual cultivation is the next phase of intensity in which there is no fallow period.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] This requires even greater nutrient and pest control inputs.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Further industrialization led to the use of monocultures, when one cultivar is planted on a large acreage.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Because of the low biodiversity, nutrient use is uniform and pests tend to build up, necessitating the greater use of pesticides and fertilizers.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Multiple cropping, in which several crops are grown sequentially in one year, and intercropping, when several crops are grown at the same time, are other kinds of annual cropping systems known as polycultures.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] In subtropical and arid environments, the timing and extent of agriculture may be limited by rainfall, either not allowing multiple annual crops in a year, or requiring irrigation.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] In all of these environments perennial crops are grown (coffee, chocolate) and systems are practiced such as agroforestry.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] In temperate environments, where ecosystems were predominantly grassland or prairie, highly productive annual farming is the dominant agricultural system.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Important categories of food crops include cereals, legumes, forage, fruits and vegetables.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Natural fibers include cotton, wool, hemp, silk and flax.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Specific crops are cultivated in distinct growing regions throughout the world.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Production is listed in millions of metric tons, based on FAO estimates.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Animal husbandry is the breeding and raising of animals for meat, milk, eggs, or wool, and for work and transport.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Working animals, including horses, mules, oxen, water buffalo, camels, llamas, alpacas, donkeys, and dogs, have for centuries been used to help cultivate fields, harvest crops, wrangle other animals, and transport farm products to buyers.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Livestock production systems can be defined based on feed source, as grassland-based, mixed, and landless.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] As of 2010, 30% of Earth's ice- and water-free area was used for producing livestock, with the sector employing approximately 1.3 billion people.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Between the 1960s and the 2000s, there was a significant increase in livestock production, both by numbers and by carcass weight, especially among beef, pigs and chickens, the latter of which had production increased by almost a factor of 10.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Non-meat animals, such as milk cows and egg-producing chickens, also showed significant production increases.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Global cattle, sheep and goat populations are expected to continue to increase sharply through 2050.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Aquaculture or fish farming, the production of fish for human consumption in confined operations, is one of the fastest growing sectors of food production, growing at an average of 9% a year between 1975 and 2007.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] During the second half of the 20th century, producers using selective breeding focused on creating livestock breeds and crossbreeds that increased production, while mostly disregarding the need to preserve genetic diversity.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] This trend has led to a significant decrease in genetic diversity and resources among livestock breeds, leading to a corresponding decrease in disease resistance and local adaptations previously found among traditional breeds.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Grassland based livestock production relies upon plant material such as shrubland, rangeland, and pastures for feeding ruminant animals.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Outside nutrient inputs may be used, however manure is returned directly to the grassland as a major nutrient source.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] This system is particularly important in areas where crop production is not feasible because of climate or soil, representing 30–40 million pastoralists.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Mixed production systems use grassland, fodder crops and grain feed crops as feed for ruminant and monogastric (one stomach; mainly chickens and pigs) livestock.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Manure is typically recycled in mixed systems as a fertilizer for crops.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Landless systems rely upon feed from outside the farm, representing the de-linking of crop and livestock production found more prevalently in Organization for Economic Co-operation and Development member countries.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Synthetic fertilizers are more heavily relied upon for crop production and manure use becomes a challenge as well as a source for pollution.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Industrialized countries use these operations to produce much of the global supplies of poultry and pork.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Scientists estimate that 75% of the growth in livestock production between 2003 and 2030 will be in confined animal feeding operations, sometimes called factory farming.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Much of this growth is happening in developing countries in Asia, with much smaller amounts of growth in Africa.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Some of the practices used in commercial livestock production, including the usage of growth hormones, are controversial.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Tillage is the practice of breaking up the soil with tools such as the plow or harrow to prepare for planting, for nutrient incorporation, or for pest control.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Tillage varies in intensity from conventional to no-till.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] It can improve productivity by warming the soil, incorporating fertilizer and controlling weeds, but also renders soil more prone to erosion, triggers the decomposition of organic matter releasing CO2, and reduces the abundance and diversity of soil organisms.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Pest control includes the management of weeds, insects, mites, and diseases.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Chemical (pesticides), biological (biocontrol), mechanical (tillage), and cultural practices are used.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Cultural practices include crop rotation, culling, cover crops, intercropping, composting, avoidance, and resistance.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Integrated pest management attempts to use all of these methods to keep pest populations below the number which would cause economic loss, and recommends pesticides as a last resort.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Nutrient management includes both the source of nutrient inputs for crop and livestock production, and the method of use of manure produced by livestock.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Nutrient inputs can be chemical inorganic fertilizers, manure, green manure, compost and minerals.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Crop nutrient use may also be managed using cultural techniques such as crop rotation or a fallow period.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Manure is used either by holding livestock where the feed crop is growing, such as in managed intensive rotational grazing, or by spreading either dry or liquid formulations of manure on cropland or pastures.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Water management is needed where rainfall is insufficient or variable, which occurs to some degree in most regions of the world.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Some farmers use irrigation to supplement rainfall.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] In other areas such as the Great Plains in the US and Canada, farmers use a fallow year to conserve soil moisture for the following year.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Recent technological innovations in precision agriculture allow for water status monitoring and automate water usage, leading to more efficient management.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Agriculture represents 70% of freshwater use worldwide.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] However, water withdrawal ratios for agriculture vary significantly by income level.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] In least developed countries and landlocked developing countries, water withdrawal ratios for agriculture are as high as 90 percent of total water withdrawals and about 60 percent in Small Island Developing States.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] According to 2014 report by the International Food Policy Research Institute, agricultural technologies will have the greatest impact on food production if adopted in combination with each other.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Payment for ecosystem services is a method of providing additional incentives to encourage farmers to conserve some aspects of the environment.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Measures might include paying for reforestation upstream of a city, to improve the supply of fresh water.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Different definitions exist for agricultural automation and for the variety of tools and technologies that are used to automate production.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] One view is that agricultural automation refers to autonomous navigation by robots without human intervention.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Alternatively, it is defined as the accomplishment of production tasks through mobile, autonomous, decision-making, mechatronic devices.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] However, FAO finds that these definitions do not capture all the aspects and forms of automation, such as robotic milking machines that are static, most motorized machinery that automates the performing of agricultural operations, and digital tools (e.g., sensors) that automate only diagnosis.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] FAO defines agricultural automation as the use of machinery and equipment in agricultural operations to improve their diagnosis, decision-making or performing, reducing the drudgery of agricultural work or improving the timeliness, and potentially the precision, of agricultural operations.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] The technological evolution in agriculture has involved a progressive move from manual tools to animal traction, to motorized mechanization, to digital equipment and finally, to robotics with artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Motorized mechanization using engine power automates the performance of agricultural operations such as ploughing and milking.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] With digital automation technologies, it also becomes possible to automate diagnosis and decision-making of agricultural operations.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] For example, autonomous crop robots can harvest and seed crops, while drones can gather information to help automate input application.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Precision agriculture often employs such automation technologies.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Motorized machines are increasingly complemented, or even superseded, by new digital equipment that automates diagnosis and decision-making.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] A conventional tractor, for example, can be converted into an automated vehicle allowing it to sow a field autonomously.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Motorized mechanization has increased significantly across the world in recent years, although reliable global data with broad country coverage exist only for tractors and only up to 2009.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Sub-Saharan Africa is the only region where the adoption of motorized mechanization has stalled over the past decades.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Automation technologies are increasingly used for managing livestock, though evidence on adoption is lacking.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Global automatic milking system sales have increased over recent years, but adoption is likely mostly in Northern Europe, and likely almost absent in low- and middle-income countries.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Automated feeding machines for both cows and poultry also exist, but data and evidence regarding their adoption trends and drivers is likewise scarce.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Measuring the overall employment impacts of agricultural automation is difficult because it requires large amounts of data tracking all the transformations and the associated reallocation of workers both upstream and downstream.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] While automation technologies reduce labor needs for the newly automated tasks, they also generate new labor demand for other tasks, such as equipment maintenance and operation.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Agricultural automation can also stimulate employment by allowing producers to expand production and by creating other agrifood systems jobs.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] This is especially true when it happens in context of rising scarcity of rural labor, as is the case in high-income countries and many middle-income countries.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] On the other hand, if forcedly promoted, for example through government subsidies in contexts of abundant rural labor, it can lead to labor displacement and falling or stagnant wages, particularly affecting poor and low-skilled workers.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Climate change and agriculture are interrelated on a global scale.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Global warming is already affecting agriculture, with effects unevenly distributed across the world.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] In a 2022 report, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change describes how human-induced warming has slowed growth of agricultural productivity over the past 50 years in mid and low latitudes.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Methane emissions have negatively impacted crop yields by increasing temperatures and surface ozone concentrations.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Warming is also negatively affecting crop and grassland quality and harvest stability.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Ocean warming has decreased sustainable yields of some wild fish populations while ocean acidification and warming have already affected farmed aquatic species.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Climate change will probably increase the risk of food insecurity for some vulnerable groups, such as the poor.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] In order to meet the demands of a growing global population, agriculture needs to produce about 50% more food, feed and fibre by 2050 compared with the volumes it generated in 2012, according to estimates by the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO).
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Achieving such objectives will place additional pressure on the world's already overstretched water, land and soil resources.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Crop alteration has been practiced by humankind for thousands of years, since the beginning of civilization.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Altering crops through breeding practices changes the genetic make-up of a plant to develop crops with more beneficial characteristics for humans, for example, larger fruits or seeds, drought-tolerance, or resistance to pests.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Significant advances in plant breeding ensued after the work of geneticist Gregor Mendel.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] His work on dominant and recessive alleles, although initially largely ignored for almost 50 years, gave plant breeders a better understanding of genetics and breeding techniques.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Crop breeding includes techniques such as plant selection with desirable traits, self-pollination and cross-pollination, and molecular techniques that genetically modify the organism.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Domestication of plants has, over the centuries increased yield, improved disease resistance and drought tolerance, eased harvest and improved the taste and nutritional value of crop plants.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Careful selection and breeding have had enormous effects on the characteristics of crop plants.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Plant selection and breeding in the 1920s and 1930s improved pasture (grasses and clover) in New Zealand.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Extensive X-ray and ultraviolet induced mutagenesis efforts (i.e. primitive genetic engineering) during the 1950s produced the modern commercial varieties of grains such as wheat, corn (maize) and barley.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] The Green Revolution popularized the use of conventional hybridization to sharply increase yield by creating "high-yielding varieties".
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] For example, average yields of corn (maize) in the US have increased from around 2.5 tons per hectare (t/ha) (40 bushels per acre) in 1900 to about 9.4 t/ha (150 bushels per acre) in 2001.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Similarly, worldwide average wheat yields have increased from less than 1 t/ha in 1900 to more than 2.5 t/ha in 1990.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] South American average wheat yields are around 2 t/ha, African under 1 t/ha, and Egypt and Arabia up to 3.5 to 4 t/ha with irrigation.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] In contrast, the average wheat yield in countries such as France is over 8 t/ha.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Variations in yields are due mainly to variation in climate, genetics, and the level of intensive farming techniques (use of fertilizers, chemical pest control, and growth control to avoid lodging).
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Investments into innovation for agriculture are long term.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] This is because it takes time for research to become commercialized and for technology to be adapted to meet multiple regions' needs, as well as meet national guidelines before being adopted and planted in a farmer's fields.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] For instance, it took at least 60 years from the introduction of hybrid corn technology before its adoption became widespread.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Agricultural innovation developed for the specific agroecological conditions of one region is not easily transferred and used in another region with different agroecological conditions.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Instead, the innovation would have to be adapted to the specific conditions of that other region and respect its biodiversity and environmental requirements and guidelines.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Some such adaptations can be seen through the steadily increasing number of plant varieties protected under the plant variety protection instrument administered by the International Union for the Protection of New Varieties of Plants (UPOV).
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Genetically modified organisms (GMO) are organisms whose genetic material has been altered by genetic engineering techniques generally known as recombinant DNA technology.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Genetic engineering has expanded the genes available to breeders to use in creating desired germlines for new crops.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Increased durability, nutritional content, insect and virus resistance and herbicide tolerance are a few of the attributes bred into crops through genetic engineering.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] For some, GMO crops cause food safety and food labeling concerns.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Numerous countries have placed restrictions on the production, import or use of GMO foods and crops.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] The Biosafety Protocol, an international treaty, regulates the trade of GMOs.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] There is ongoing discussion regarding the labeling of foods made from GMOs, and the EU has had GMO food labeling requirements since 1997.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] As of 2022, the United States requires food containing GMO ingredients to be labeled as well.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Herbicide-resistant seeds have a gene implanted into their genome that allows the plants to tolerate exposure to herbicides, including glyphosate.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] These seeds allow the farmer to grow a crop that can be sprayed with herbicides to control weeds without harming the resistant crop.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Herbicide-tolerant crops are used by farmers worldwide.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] With the increasing use of herbicide-tolerant crops, comes an increase in the use of glyphosate-based herbicide sprays.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] In some areas glyphosate resistant weeds have developed, causing farmers to switch to other herbicides.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Some studies also link widespread glyphosate usage to iron deficiencies in some crops, which is both a crop production and a nutritional quality concern, with potential economic and health implications.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Other GMO crops used by growers include insect-resistant crops, which have a gene from the soil bacterium *Bacillus thuringiensis* (Bt), which produces a toxin specific to insects.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] Some believe that similar or better pest-resistance traits can be acquired through traditional breeding practices, and resistance to various pests can be gained through hybridization or cross-pollination with wild species.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p01] In some cases, wild species are the primary source of resistance traits; some tomato cultivars that have gained resistance to at least 19 diseases did so through crossing with wild populations of tomatoes.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Agriculture is both a cause of environmental degradation and sensitive to environmental degradation, such as biodiversity loss, desertification, soil degradation and climate change, which cause decreases in crop yield.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Agriculture is one of the most important drivers of environmental pressures, particularly habitat change, climate change, water use and toxic emissions.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Agriculture is the main source of toxins released into the environment, including insecticides, especially those used on cotton.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] The 2011 UNEP Green Economy report stated that agricultural operations produced some 13 percent of anthropogenic global greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] This includes gases from the use of inorganic fertilizers, agro-chemical pesticides, and herbicides, as well as fossil fuel-energy inputs.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Agriculture imposes multiple external costs upon society through effects such as pesticide damage to nature (especially herbicides and insecticides), nutrient runoff, excessive water usage, and loss of natural environment.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] A 2000 assessment of agriculture in the UK determined total external costs for 1996 of £2,343 million, or £208 per hectare.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] A 2005 analysis of these costs in the US concluded that cropland imposes approximately $5 to $16 billion ($30 to $96 per hectare), while livestock production imposes $714 million.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Both studies, which focused solely on the fiscal impacts, concluded that more should be done to internalize external costs.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Neither included subsidies in their analysis, but they noted that subsidies also influence the cost of agriculture to society.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Agriculture seeks to increase yield and to reduce costs, often employing measures that cut biodiversity to very low levels.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Yield increases with inputs such as fertilizers and removal of pathogens, predators, and competitors (such as weeds).
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Costs decrease with increasing scale of farm units, such as making fields larger; this means removing hedges, ditches and other areas of habitat.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Pesticides kill insects, plants and fungi.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Effective yields fall with on-farm losses, which may be caused by poor production practices during harvesting, handling, and storage.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] The environmental effects of climate change show that research on pests and diseases that do not generally afflict areas is essential.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] In 2021, farmers discovered stem rust on wheat in the Champagne area of France, a disease that had previously only occurred in Morocco for 20 to 30 years.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Because of climate change, insects that used to die off over the winter are now alive and multiplying.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] A senior UN official, Henning Steinfeld, said that "Livestock are one of the most significant contributors to today's most serious environmental problems".
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Livestock production occupies 70% of all land used for agriculture, or 30% of the land surface of the planet.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] It is one of the largest sources of greenhouse gases, responsible for 18% of the world's greenhouse gas emissions as measured in CO2 equivalents.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] By comparison, all transportation emits 13.5% of the CO2.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] (This comparison later turned out to be an apples-and-oranges analogy.) It produces 65% of human-related nitrous oxide (which has 296 times the global warming potential of CO2) and 37% of all human-induced methane (which is 23 times as warming as CO2.) It also generates 64% of the ammonia emission.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Livestock expansion is cited as a key factor driving deforestation; in the Amazon basin 70% of previously forested area is now occupied by pastures and the remainder used for feed crops.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Through deforestation and land degradation, livestock is also driving reductions in biodiversity.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] A well documented phenomenon is woody plant encroachment, caused by overgrazing in rangelands.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Land transformation, the use of land to yield goods and services, is the most substantial way humans alter the Earth's ecosystems, and is the driving force causing biodiversity loss.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Estimates of the amount of land transformed by humans vary from 39 to 50%.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] It is estimated that 24% of land globally experiences land degradation, a long-term decline in ecosystem function and productivity, with cropland being disproportionately affected.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Land management is the driving factor behind degradation; 1.5 billion people rely upon the degrading land.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Degradation can be through deforestation, desertification, soil erosion, mineral depletion, acidification, or salinization.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] In 2021, the global agricultural land area was 4.79 billion hectares (ha), down 2 percent, or 0.09 billion ha compared with 2000.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Between 2000 and 2021, roughly two-thirds of agricultural land were used for permanent meadows and pastures (3.21 billion ha in 2021), which declined by 5 percent (0.17 billion ha).
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] One-third of the total agricultural land was cropland (1.58 billion ha in 2021), which increased by 6 percent (0.09 billion ha).
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Within the U.S., total agricultural land use is estimated to be 56%, and including grazing, animal agriculture constitutes around 80% of agricultural land.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Eutrophication, excessive nutrient enrichment in aquatic ecosystems resulting in algal blooms and anoxia, leads to fish kills, loss of biodiversity, and renders water unfit for drinking and other industrial uses.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Excessive fertilization and manure application to cropland, as well as high livestock stocking densities cause nutrient (mainly nitrogen and phosphorus) runoff and leaching from agricultural land.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] These nutrients are major nonpoint pollutants contributing to eutrophication of aquatic ecosystems and pollution of groundwater, with harmful effects on human populations.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Fertilizers also reduce terrestrial biodiversity by increasing competition for light, favoring those species that are able to benefit from the added nutrients.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Agriculture simultaneously is facing growing freshwater demand and precipitation anomalies (droughts, floods, and extreme rainfall and weather events) on rainfed areas fields and grazing lands.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Agriculture accounts for 70 percent of withdrawals of freshwater resources, and an estimated 41 percent of current global irrigation water use occurs at the expense of environmental flow requirements.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Within the U.S., agriculture accounts for about 80% of total water consumption, with animal agriculture making up half of agricultural consumption (around 40%).
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] It is long known that aquifers in areas as diverse as northern China, the Upper Ganges and the western US are being depleted, and new research extends these problems to aquifers in Iran, Mexico and Saudi Arabia.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Increasing pressure is being placed on water resources by industry and urban areas, meaning that water scarcity is increasing and agriculture is facing the challenge of producing more food for the world's growing population with reduced water resources.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] While industrial withdrawals have declined in the past few decades and municipal withdrawals have increased only marginally since 2010, agricultural withdrawals have continued to grow at an ever faster pace.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Agricultural water usage can also cause major environmental problems, including the destruction of natural wetlands, the spread of water-borne diseases, and land degradation through salinization and waterlogging, when irrigation is performed incorrectly.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Pesticide use has increased since 1950 to 2.5 million short tons annually worldwide, yet crop loss from pests has remained relatively constant.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] The World Health Organization estimated in 1992 that three million pesticide poisonings occur annually, causing 220,000 deaths.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Pesticides select for pesticide resistance in the pest population, leading to a condition termed the "pesticide treadmill" in which pest resistance warrants the development of a new pesticide.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] An alternative argument is that the way to "save the environment" and prevent famine is by using pesticides and intensive high yield farming, a view exemplified by a quote heading the Center for Global Food Issues website: 'Growing more per acre leaves more land for nature'.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] However, critics argue that a trade-off between the environment and a need for food is not inevitable, and that pesticides can replace good agronomic practices such as crop rotation.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] The Push–pull agricultural pest management technique involves intercropping, using plant aromas to repel pests from crops (push) and to lure them to a place from which they can then be removed (pull).
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Agriculture contributes towards climate change through greenhouse gas emissions and by the conversion of non-agricultural land such as forests into agricultural land.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] The agriculture, forestry and land use sector contribute between 13% and 21% of global greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Emissions of nitrous oxide, methane make up over half of total greenhouse gas emission from agriculture.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Animal husbandry is a major source of greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Approximately 57% of global GHG emissions from the production of food are from the production of animal-based food while plant-based foods contribute 29% and the remaining 14% is for other utilizations.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Farmland management and land-use change represented major shares of total emissions (38% and 29%, respectively), whereas rice and beef were the largest contributing plant- and animal-based commodities (12% and 25%, respectively).
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] South and Southeast Asia and South America were the largest emitters of production-based GHGs.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Climate change put significant part of crops in danger already at 1.5 degrees of warming.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] While in North America, Europe and central Asia the share of endangered crops is relatively little at this level of warming, in the Middle east and North Africa region for example, close to 50% of cropland is in danger.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] With further temperature rise the risk increase in all regions, in some more, in some less.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Globally the cropland area in safe climatic zone decrease for all the major crop groups as warming exceed 1.5 degrees.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Current farming methods have resulted in over-stretched water resources, high levels of erosion and reduced soil fertility.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] There is not enough water to continue farming using current practices; therefore how water, land, and ecosystem resources are used to boost crop yields must be reconsidered.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] A solution would be to give value to ecosystems, recognizing environmental and livelihood tradeoffs, and balancing the rights of a variety of users and interests.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Inequities that result when such measures are adopted would need to be addressed, such as the reallocation of water from poor to rich, the clearing of land to make way for more productive farmland, or the preservation of a wetland system that limits fishing rights.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Technological advancements help provide farmers with tools and resources to make farming more sustainable.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Technology permits innovations like conservation tillage, a farming process which helps prevent land loss to erosion, reduces water pollution, and enhances carbon sequestration.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Agricultural automation can help address some of the challenges associated with climate change and thus facilitate adaptation efforts.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] For example, the application of digital automation technologies (e.g. in precision agriculture) can improve resource-use efficiency in conditions which are increasingly constrained for agricultural producers.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Moreover, when applied to sensing and early warning, they can help address the uncertainty and unpredictability of weather conditions associated with accelerating climate change.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Other potential sustainable practices include conservation agriculture, agroforestry, improved grazing, avoided grassland conversion, and biochar.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Current mono-crop farming practices in the United States preclude widespread adoption of sustainable practices, such as 2–3 crop rotations that incorporate grass or hay with annual crops, unless negative emission goals such as soil carbon sequestration become policy.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] The food demand of Earth's projected population, with current climate change predictions, could be satisfied by improvement of agricultural methods, expansion of agricultural areas, and a sustainability-oriented consumer mindset.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Since the 1940s, agricultural productivity has increased dramatically, due largely to the increased use of energy-intensive mechanization, fertilizers and pesticides.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] The vast majority of this energy input comes from fossil fuel sources.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Between the 1960s and the 1980s, the Green Revolution transformed agriculture around the globe, with world grain production increasing significantly (between 70% and 390% for wheat and 60% to 150% for rice, depending on geographic area) as world population doubled.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Heavy reliance on petrochemicals has raised concerns that oil shortages could increase costs and reduce agricultural output.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Industrialized agriculture depends on fossil fuels in two fundamental ways: direct consumption on the farm and manufacture of inputs used on the farm.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Direct consumption includes the use of lubricants and fuels to operate farm vehicles and machinery.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Indirect consumption includes the manufacture of fertilizers, pesticides, and farm machinery.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] In particular, the production of nitrogen fertilizer can account for over half of agricultural energy usage.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Together, direct and indirect consumption by US farms accounts for about 2% of the nation's energy use.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Direct and indirect energy consumption by US farms peaked in 1979, and has since gradually declined.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Food systems encompass not just agriculture but off-farm processing, packaging, transporting, marketing, consumption, and disposal of food and food-related items.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Agriculture accounts for less than one-fifth of food system energy use in the US.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Plastic products are used extensively in agriculture, including to increase crop yields and improve the efficiency of water and agrichemical use.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] "Agriplastic" products include films to cover greenhouses and tunnels, mulch to cover soil (e.g. to suppress weeds, conserve water, increase soil temperature and aid fertilizer application), shade cloth, pesticide containers, seedling trays, protective mesh and irrigation tubing.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] The polymers most commonly used in these products are low-density polyethylene (LPDE), linear low-density polyethylene (LLDPE), polypropylene (PP) and polyvinyl chloride (PVC).
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] The total amount of plastics used in agriculture is difficult to quantify.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] A 2012 study reported that almost 6.5 million tonnes per year were consumed globally while a later study estimated that global demand in 2015 was between 7.3 million and 9 million tonnes.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Widespread use of plastic mulch and lack of systematic collection and management have led to the generation of large amounts of mulch residue.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Weathering and degradation eventually cause the mulch to fragment.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] These fragments and larger pieces of plastic accumulate in soil.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Mulch residue has been measured at levels of 50 to 260 kg per hectare in topsoil in areas where mulch use dates back more than 10 years, which confirms that mulching is a major source of both microplastic and macroplastic soil contamination.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Agricultural plastics, especially plastic films, are not easy to recycle because of high contamination levels (up to 40–50% by weight contamination by pesticides, fertilizers, soil and debris, moist vegetation, silage juice water, and UV stabilizers) and collection difficulties .
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Therefore, they are often buried or abandoned in fields and watercourses or burned.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] These disposal practices lead to soil degradation and can result in contamination of soils and leakage of microplastics into the marine environment as a result of precipitation run-off and tidal washing.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] In addition, additives in residual plastic film (such as UV and thermal stabilizers) may have deleterious effects on crop growth, soil structure, nutrient transport and salt levels.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] There is a risk that plastic mulch will deteriorate soil quality, deplete soil organic matter stocks, increase soil water repellence and emit greenhouse gases.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Microplastics released through fragmentation of agricultural plastics can absorb and concentrate contaminants capable of being passed up the trophic chain.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Agricultural economics is economics as it relates to the "production, distribution and consumption of [agricultural] goods and services".
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Combining agricultural production with general theories of marketing and business as a discipline of study began in the late 1800s, and grew significantly through the 20th century.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] In the United States, and elsewhere, food costs attributed to food processing, distribution, and agricultural marketing, sometimes referred to as the value chain, have risen while the costs attributed to farming have declined.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] This is related to the greater efficiency of farming, combined with the increased level of value addition (e.g. more highly processed products) provided by the supply chain.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Market concentration has increased in the sector as well, and although the total effect of the increased market concentration is likely increased efficiency, the changes redistribute economic surplus from producers (farmers) and consumers, and may have negative implications for rural communities.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] National government policies, such as taxation, subsidies, tariffs and others, can significantly change the economic marketplace for agricultural products.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Since at least the 1960s, a combination of trade restrictions, exchange rate policies and subsidies have affected farmers in both the developing and the developed world.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] In the 1980s, non-subsidized farmers in developing countries experienced adverse effects from national policies that created artificially low global prices for farm products.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Between the mid-1980s and the early 2000s, several international agreements limited agricultural tariffs, subsidies and other trade restrictions.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] However, as of 2009, there was still a significant amount of policy-driven distortion in global agricultural product prices.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] The three agricultural products with the most trade distortion were sugar, milk and rice, mainly due to taxation.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Among the oilseeds, sesame had the most taxation, but overall, feed grains and oilseeds had much lower levels of taxation than livestock products.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Since the 1980s, policy-driven distortions have decreases more among livestock products than crops during the worldwide reforms in agricultural policy.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Despite this progress, certain crops, such as cotton, still see subsidies in developed countries artificially deflating global prices, causing hardship in developing countries with non-subsidized farmers.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Unprocessed commodities such as corn, soybeans, and cattle are generally graded to indicate quality, affecting the price the producer receives.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Commodities are generally reported by production quantities, such as volume, number or weight.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Agricultural science is a broad multidisciplinary field of biology that encompasses the parts of exact, natural, economic and social sciences used in the practice and understanding of agriculture.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] The scientific study of agriculture began in the 18th century, when Johann Friedrich Mayer conducted experiments on the use of gypsum (hydrated calcium sulphate) as a fertilizer.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Research became more systematic when in 1843, John Lawes and Henry Gilbert began a set of long-term agronomy field experiments at Rothamsted Research Station in England; some of them, such as the Park Grass Experiment, are still running.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] In America, the Hatch Act of 1887 provided funding for what it was the first to call "agricultural science", driven by farmers' interest in fertilizers.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Agricultural policy is the set of government decisions and actions relating to domestic agriculture and imports of foreign agricultural products.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Governments usually implement agricultural policies with the goal of achieving a specific outcome in the domestic agricultural product markets.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Agricultural policy can also touch on food quality, ensuring that the food supply is of a consistent and known quality, food security, ensuring that the food supply meets the population's needs, and conservation.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Policy programs can range from financial programs, such as subsidies, to encouraging producers to enroll in voluntary quality assurance programs.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] A 2021 report finds that globally, support to agricultural producers accounts for almost US$540 billion a year.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] This amounts to 15 percent of total agricultural production value, and is heavily biased towards measures that are leading to inefficiency, as well as are unequally distributed and harmful for the environment and human health.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Crop use in animal agriculture accounts for one form of inefficiency.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Animal agriculture's estimated land use to produce one kilocalorie or gram of protein is 50 to 100 times that of plant-based alternatives.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Furthermore, the larger the livestock, the lower the energy efficiency (kilocalories obtained relative to kilocalories the animal consumes).
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] For instance, beef's energy efficiency is estimated to be 2%.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] There are many influences on the creation of agricultural policy, including consumers, agribusiness, trade lobbies and other groups.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Agribusiness interests hold a large amount of influence over policy making, in the form of lobbying and campaign contributions.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Political action groups, including those interested in environmental issues and labor unions, also provide influence, as do lobbying organizations representing individual agricultural commodities.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] The Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO) leads international efforts to defeat hunger and provides a forum for the negotiation of global agricultural regulations and agreements.
[src:habitat-destruction/agriculture-p02] Samuel Jutzi, director of FAO's animal production and health division, states that lobbying by large corporations has stopped reforms that would improve human health and the environment.
[src:habitat-destruction/arkive] The project was an initiative of Wildscreen, a UK-registered educational charity, based in Bristol.
[src:habitat-destruction/arkive] The technical platform was created by Hewlett-Packard, as part of the HP Labs' Digital Media Systems research programme.
[src:habitat-destruction/arkive] It was a member of the Institutional Council of the Encyclopedia of Life.
[src:habitat-destruction/arkive] Two ARKive layers for Google Earth, featuring endangered species and species in the Gulf of Mexico were produced by Google Earth Outreach.
[src:habitat-destruction/arkive] The first of these was launched in April 2008 by Wildscreen's Patron, Sir David Attenborough.
[src:habitat-destruction/arkive] Due to lack of funding, the website was closed on 15 February 2019 and the media collection taken offline.
[src:habitat-destruction/arkive] Its successor, Wildscreen ARK (https://wildscreenark.org/), was launched in February 2024.
[src:habitat-destruction/arkive] The project formally was launched on 20 May 2003 by its patron, the UK-based natural history presenter, Sir David Attenborough, a long-standing colleague and friend of its chief instigator, the late Christopher Parsons, a former Head of the BBC Natural History Unit.
[src:habitat-destruction/arkive] Parsons never lived to see the fruition of the project, succumbing to cancer in November 2002 at the age of 70.
[src:habitat-destruction/arkive] Parsons identified a need to provide a centralised safe haven for wildlife films and photographs after discovering that many such records are held in scattered, non-indexed, collections, often with little or no public access, and sometimes in conditions that could lead to loss or damage.
[src:habitat-destruction/arkive] He believed the records could be a powerful force in building environmental awareness by bringing scientific names to life.
[src:habitat-destruction/arkive] He also saw their preservation as an important educational resource and conservation tool, not at least because extinction rates and habitat destruction could mean that images and sounds might be the only legacy of some species' existence.
[src:habitat-destruction/arkive] Media was digitised to the highest available quality without compression and encoded to open standards.
[src:habitat-destruction/arkive] A prototype site was online as early as April 1999.
[src:habitat-destruction/arkive] There were several design iterations before the formal launch.
[src:habitat-destruction/arkive] By the launch date, the project team had researched, catalogued, copied, described and authenticated image, sound and fact files of 1,000 animals, plants and fungi, many of them critically endangered.
[src:habitat-destruction/arkive] More multi-media profiles are added every month, starting with British flora and fauna and with species included on the Red List – that is, species that are believed to be closest to extinction, according to research by the World Conservation Union.
[src:habitat-destruction/arkive] By January 2006, the database had grown to 2,000 species, 15,000 still images and more than 50 hours of videos.
[src:habitat-destruction/arkive] By 2010, over 5,500 donors had contributed 70,000 film clips and photos of more than 12,000 species.
[src:habitat-destruction/arkive] In February 2019, Wildscreen announced that they "...have had to make the very hard decision to close the Arkive website on 15 February 2019", due to funding issues.
[src:habitat-destruction/arkive] The site was *Sunday Times* website of the year for 2005.
[src:habitat-destruction/arkive] It was a 2010 Webby Award honouree for its outstanding calibre of work, in the 'Education' category, and a 2010 Association of Educational Publishers 'Distinguished Achievement Award' winner, in the category for websites for 9-to-12-year-olds.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Humans contribute to habitat destruction through the use of natural resources, agriculture, industrial production and urbanization (urban sprawl).
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Other activities include mining, logging, and trawling.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Environmental factors can contribute to habitat destruction more indirectly.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Geological processes, climate change, introduction of invasive species, ecosystem nutrient depletion, water and noise pollution are some of the examples.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Loss of habitat can be preceded by an initial habitat fragmentation.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Fragmentation and loss of habitat have become one of the most important topics of research in ecology as they are major threats to the survival of endangered species.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Biodiversity hotspots are chiefly tropical regions that feature high concentrations of endemic species and, when all hotspots are combined, may contain over half of the world's terrestrial species.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] These hotspots are suffering from habitat loss and destruction.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Most of the natural habitat on islands and in areas of high human population density has already been destroyed (WRI, 2003).
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Islands suffering extreme habitat destruction include New Zealand, Madagascar, the Philippines, and Japan.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] South and East Asia—especially China, India, Malaysia, Indonesia, and Japan—and many areas in West Africa have extremely dense human populations that allow little room for natural habitat.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Marine areas close to highly populated coastal cities also face degradation of their coral reefs or other marine habitat.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Forest City, a township in southern Malaysia built on Environmentally Sensitive Area (ESA) Rank 1 wetland is one such example, with irreversible reclamation proceeding prior to environmental impact assessments and approvals.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Other such areas include the eastern coasts of Asia and Africa, northern coasts of South America, and the Caribbean Sea and its associated islands.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Regions of unsustainable agriculture or unstable governments, which may go hand-in-hand, typically experience high rates of habitat destruction.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] South Asia, Central America, Sub-Saharan Africa, and the Amazonian tropical rainforest areas of South America are the main regions with unsustainable agricultural practices and/or government mismanagement.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Areas of high agricultural output tend to have the highest extent of habitat destruction.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] In the U.S., less than 25% of native vegetation remains in many parts of the East and Midwest.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Only 15% of land area remains unmodified by human activities in all of Europe.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Currently, changes occurring in different environments around the world are changing the specific geographical habitats that are suitable for plants to grow.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Therefore, the ability for plants to migrate to suitable environment areas will have a strong impact on the distribution of plant diversity.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] However, at the moment, the rates of plant migration that are influenced by habitat loss and fragmentation are not as well understood as they could be.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Tropical rainforests have received most of the attention concerning the destruction of habitat.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] From the approximately 16 million square kilometers of tropical rainforest habitat that originally existed worldwide, less than 9 million square kilometers remain today.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] The current rate of deforestation is 160,000 square kilometers per year, which equates to a loss of approximately 1% of original forest habitat each year.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Other forest ecosystems have suffered as much or more destruction as tropical rainforests.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Deforestation for farming and logging have severely disturbed at least 94% of temperate broadleaf forests; many old growth forest stands have lost more than 98% of their previous area because of human activities.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Tropical deciduous dry forests are easier to clear and burn and are more suitable for agriculture and cattle ranching than tropical rainforests; consequently, less than 0.1% of dry forests in Central America's Pacific Coast and less than 8% in Madagascar remain from their original extents.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Plains and desert areas have been degraded to a lesser extent.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Only 10–20% of the world's drylands, which include temperate grasslands, savannas, and shrublands, scrub, and deciduous forests, have been somewhat degraded.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] But included in that 10–20% of land is the approximately 9 million square kilometers of seasonally dry-lands that humans have converted to deserts through the process of desertification.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] The tallgrass prairies of North America, on the other hand, have less than 3% of natural habitat remaining that has not been converted to farmland.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Wetlands and marine areas have endured high levels of habitat destruction.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] More than 50% of wetlands in the U.S. have been destroyed in just the last 200 years.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Between 60% and 70% of European wetlands have been completely destroyed.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] In the United Kingdom, there has been an increase in demand for coastal housing and tourism which has caused a decline in marine habitats over the last 60 years.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] The rising sea levels and temperatures have caused soil erosion, coastal flooding, and loss of quality in the UK marine ecosystem.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] About one-fifth (20%) of marine coastal areas have been highly modified by humans.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] One-fifth of coral reefs have also been destroyed, and another fifth has been severely degraded by overfishing, pollution, and invasive species; 90% of the Philippines' coral reefs alone have been destroyed.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Finally, over 35% of the mangrove ecosystems worldwide have been destroyed.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Habitat destruction through natural processes such as volcanism, fire, and climate change is well documented in the fossil record.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] One study shows that habitat fragmentation of tropical rainforests in Euramerica 300 million years ago led to a great loss of amphibian diversity, but simultaneously the drier climate spurred on a burst of diversity among reptiles.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Gamma ray bursts are potential cause for the habitat destruction by depleating ozone layer in upper atmosphere of a planet.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Habitat destruction caused by humans includes land conversion from forests, etc. to arable land, urban sprawl, infrastructure development, and other anthropogenic changes to the characteristics of land.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Habitat degradation, fragmentation, and pollution are aspects of habitat destruction caused by humans that do not necessarily involve over destruction of habitat, yet result in habitat collapse.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Desertification, deforestation, and coral reef degradation are specific types of habitat destruction for those areas (deserts, forests, coral reefs).
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Studies show that deforestation in forests, desertification in drylands, and the degradation of coral reefs in marine environments each contribute to habitat destruction and the loss of biodiversity.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] The forces that cause humans to destroy habitat are known as *drivers* of habitat destruction.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Demographic, economic, sociopolitical, scientific and technological, and cultural drivers all contribute to habitat destruction.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Most of the exponential human population growth worldwide is occurring in or close to biodiversity hotspots.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] This may explain why human population density accounts for 87.9% of the variation in numbers of threatened species across 114 countries, providing indisputable evidence that people play the largest role in decreasing biodiversity.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] The boom in human population and migration of people into such species-rich regions are making conservation efforts not only more urgent but also more likely to conflict with local human interests.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] The high local population density in such areas is directly correlated to the poverty status of the local people, most of whom lacking an education and family planning.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] The main economic factors included commercialization and growth of timber markets (68%), which are driven by national and international demands; urban industrial growth (38%); low domestic costs for land, labor, fuel, and timber (32%); and increases in product prices mainly for cash crops (25%).
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] The main technological factor was the poor application of technology in the wood industry (45%), which leads to wasteful logging practices.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Within the broad category of cultural and sociopolitical factors are public attitudes and values (63%), individual/household behavior (53%), public unconcern toward forest environments (43%), missing basic values (36%), and unconcern by individuals (32%).
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Demographic factors were the in-migration of colonizing settlers into sparsely populated forest areas (38%) and growing population density—a result of the first factor—in those areas (25%).
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] The rate of global tree cover loss has approximately doubled since 2001, to an annual loss approaching an area the size of Italy.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] The period since 1950 has brought "the most rapid transformation of the human relationship with the natural world in the history of humankind".
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Almost one-third of the world's forests, and almost two-thirds of its grassland, have been lost to human agriculture—which now occupies almost half the world's habitable land.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Geist and Lambin (2002) assessed 152 case studies of net losses of tropical forest cover to determine any patterns in the proximate and underlying causes of tropical deforestation.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Their results, yielded as percentages of the case studies in which each parameter was a significant factor, provide a quantitative prioritization of which proximate and underlying causes were the most significant.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] The proximate causes were clustered into broad categories of agricultural expansion (96%), infrastructure expansion (72%), and wood extraction (67%).
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Therefore, according to this study, forest conversion to agriculture is the main land use change responsible for tropical deforestation.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] One result is that shifting cultivation is not the primary cause of deforestation in all world regions, while transport extension (including the construction of new roads) is the largest single proximate factor responsible for deforestation.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Habitat size and numbers of species are systematically related.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Physically larger species and those living at lower latitudes or in forests or oceans are more sensitive to reduction in habitat area.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Conversion to "trivial" standardized ecosystems (e.g., monoculture following deforestation) effectively destroys habitat for the more diverse species.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Even the simplest forms of agriculture affect diversity – through clearing or draining the land, discouraging weeds and pests, and encouraging just a limited set of domesticated plant and animal species.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] There are also feedbacks and interactions among the proximate and underlying causes of deforestation that can amplify the process.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Road construction has the largest feedback effect, because it interacts with—and leads to—the establishment of new settlements and more people, which causes a growth in wood (logging) and food markets.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Growth in these markets, in turn, progresses the commercialization of agriculture and logging industries.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] When these industries become commercialized, they must become more efficient by utilizing larger or more modern machinery that often has a worse effect on the habitat than traditional farming and logging methods.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Either way, more land is cleared more rapidly for commercial markets.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] This common feedback example manifests just how closely related the proximate and underlying causes are to each other.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Climate change contributes to destruction of some habitats, endangering various species.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Habitat fragmentation describes the emergence of discontinuities (fragmentation) in an organism's preferred environment (habitat), causing population fragmentation and ecosystem decay.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] More specifically, habitat fragmentation is a process by which large and contiguous habitats get divided into smaller, isolated patches of habitats.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] When a habitat is destroyed, the carrying capacity for indigenous plants, animals, and other organisms is reduced so that populations decline, sometimes up to the level of extinction.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Habitat loss is perhaps the greatest threat to organisms and biodiversity.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Temple (1986) found that 82% of endangered bird species were significantly threatened by habitat loss.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Most amphibian species are also threatened by native habitat loss, and some species are now only breeding in modified habitat.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Endemic organisms with limited ranges are most affected by habitat destruction, mainly because these organisms are not found anywhere else in the world, and thus have less chance of recovering.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Many endemic organisms have very specific requirements for their survival that can only be found within a certain ecosystem, resulting in their extinction.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Extinction may also take place very long after the destruction of habitat, a phenomenon known as extinction debt.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Habitat destruction can also decrease the range of certain organism populations.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] This can result in the reduction of genetic diversity and perhaps the production of infertile youths, as these organisms would have a higher possibility of mating with related organisms within their population, or different species.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] One of the most famous examples is the impact upon China's giant panda, once found in many areas of Sichuan.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Now it is only found in fragmented and isolated regions in the southwest of the country, as a result of widespread deforestation in the 20th century.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] As habitat destruction of an area occurs, the species diversity offsets from a combination of habitat generalists and specialists to a population primarily consisting of generalist species.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Invasive species are frequently generalists that are able to survive in much more diverse habitats.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Habitat destruction leading to climate change offsets the balance of species keeping up with the extinction threshold leading to a higher likelihood of extinction.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Habitat loss is one of the main environmental causes of the decline of biodiversity on local, regional, and global scales.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Many believe that habitat fragmentation is also a threat to biodiversity however some believe that it is secondary to habitat loss.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] The reduction of the amount of habitat available results in specific landscapes that are made of isolated patches of suitable habitat throughout a hostile environment/matrix.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] This process is generally due to pure habitat loss as well as fragmentation effects.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Pure habitat loss refers to changes occurring in the composition of the landscape that causes a decrease in individuals.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Fragmentation effects refer to an addition of effects occurring due to the habitat changes.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Habitat loss can result in negative effects on the dynamic of species richness.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] The order Hymenoptera is a diverse group of plant pollinators who are highly susceptible to the negative effects of habitat loss, this could result in a domino effect between the plant-pollinator interactions leading to major conservation implications within this group.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] It is observed from the worlds longest running fragmentation experiment over 35 years that habitat fragmentation has caused a decrease in biodiversity from 13% to 75%.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Habitat destruction can vastly increase an area's vulnerability to natural disasters like flood and drought, crop failure, spread of disease, and water contamination.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] On the other hand, a healthy ecosystem with good management practices can reduce the chance of these events happening, or will at least mitigate adverse impacts.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Eliminating swamps—the habitat of pests such as mosquitoes—has contributed to the prevention of diseases such as malaria.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Completely depriving an infectious agent (such as a virus) of its habitat—by vaccination, for example—can result in eradicating that infectious agent.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Agricultural land can suffer from the destruction of the surrounding landscape.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Over the past 50 years, the destruction of habitat surrounding agricultural land has degraded approximately 40% of agricultural land worldwide via erosion, salinization, compaction, nutrient depletion, pollution, and urbanization.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Humans also lose direct uses of natural habitat when habitat is destroyed.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Aesthetic uses such as birdwatching, recreational uses like hunting and fishing, and ecotourism usually rely upon relatively undisturbed habitat.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Many people value the complexity of the natural world and express concern at the loss of natural habitats and of animal or plant species worldwide.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Probably the most profound impact that habitat destruction has on people is the loss of many valuable ecosystem services.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Habitat destruction has altered nitrogen, phosphorus, sulfur, and carbon cycles, which has increased the frequency and severity of acid rain, algal blooms, and fish kills in rivers and oceans and contributed tremendously to global climate change.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] One ecosystem service whose significance is becoming better understood is climate regulation.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] The loss of trees from tropical rainforests alone represents a substantial diminishing of Earth's ability to produce oxygen and to use up carbon dioxide.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] These services are becoming even more important as increasing carbon dioxide levels is one of the main contributors to global climate change.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] The loss of biodiversity may not directly affect humans, but the indirect effects of losing many species as well as the diversity of ecosystems in general are enormous.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] When biodiversity is lost, the environment loses many species that perform valuable and unique roles in the ecosystem.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] The environment and all its inhabitants rely on biodiversity to recover from extreme environmental conditions.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] When too much biodiversity is lost, a catastrophic event such as an earthquake, flood, or volcanic eruption could cause an ecosystem to crash, and humans would obviously suffer from that.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] The negative effects of habitat destruction usually impact rural populations more directly than urban populations.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Across the globe, poor people suffer the most when natural habitat is destroyed, because less natural habitat means fewer natural resources *per capita*, yet wealthier people and countries can simply pay more to continue to receive more than their *per capita* share of natural resources.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Another way to view the negative effects of habitat destruction is to look at the opportunity cost of destroying a given habitat.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] In other words, what do people lose out on with the removal of a given habitat?
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] A country may increase its food supply by converting forest land to row-crop agriculture, but the value of the same land may be much larger when it can supply natural resources or services such as clean water, timber, ecotourism, or flood regulation and drought control.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] The rapid expansion of the global human population is increasing the world's food requirement substantially.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Simple logic dictates that more people will require more food.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] In fact, as the world's population increases dramatically, agricultural output will need to increase by at least 50%, over the next 30 years.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] In the past, continually moving to new land and soils provided a boost in food production to meet the global food demand.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] That easy fix will no longer be available, however, as more than 98% of all land suitable for agriculture is already in use or degraded beyond repair.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] The impending global food crisis will be a major source of habitat destruction.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Commercial farmers are going to become desperate to produce more food from the same amount of land, so they will use more fertilizers and show less concern for the environment to meet the market demand.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Others will seek out new land or will convert other land-uses to agriculture.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Agricultural intensification will become widespread at the cost of the environment and its inhabitants.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Species will be pushed out of their habitat either directly by habitat destruction or indirectly by fragmentation, degradation, or pollution.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Any efforts to protect the world's remaining natural habitat and biodiversity will compete directly with humans' growing demand for natural resources, especially new agricultural lands.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Attempts to address habitat destruction are in international policy commitments embodied by Sustainable Development Goal 15 "Life on Land" and Sustainable Development Goal 14 "Life Below Water".
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] However, the United Nations Environment Programme report on "Making Peace with Nature" released in 2021 found that most of these efforts had failed to meet their internationally agreed upon goals.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Tropical deforestation: In most cases of tropical deforestation, three to four underlying causes are driving two to three proximate causes.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] This means that a universal policy for controlling tropical deforestation would not be able to address the unique combination of proximate and underlying causes of deforestation in each country.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Before any local, national, or international deforestation policies are written and enforced, governmental leaders must acquire a detailed understanding of the complex combination of proximate causes and underlying driving forces of deforestation in a given area or country.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] This concept, along with many other results of tropical deforestation from the Geist and Lambin study, can easily be applied to habitat destruction in general.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Shoreline erosion: Coastal erosion is a natural process as storms, waves, tides and other water level changes occur.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Shoreline stabilization can be done by barriers between land and water such as seawalls and bulkheads.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Living shorelines are gaining attention as a new stabilization method.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Preventing an area from losing its specialist species to generalist invasive species depends on the extent of the habitat destruction that has already taken place.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] In areas where the habitat is relatively undisturbed, halting further habitat destruction may be enough.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] In areas where habitat destruction is more extreme (fragmentation or patch loss), restoration ecology may be needed.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Education of the general public is possibly the best way to prevent further human habitat destruction.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Changing the dull creep of environmental impacts from being viewed as acceptable to being seen a reason for change to more sustainable practices.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Education about the necessity of family planning to slow population growth is important as greater population leads to greater human caused habitat destruction.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Habitat restoration can also take place through the following processes; extending habitats or repairing habitats.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Extending habitats aims to counteract habitat loss and fragmentation whereas repairing habitats counteracts degradation.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] The preservation and creation of habitat corridors can link isolated populations and increase pollination.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Corridors are also known to reduce the negative impacts of habitat destruction.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Governmental leaders need to take action by addressing the underlying driving forces, rather than merely regulating the proximate causes.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Protecting remaining intact sections of natural habitat.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Finding ecological ways to increase agricultural output without increasing the total land in production.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Reducing human population and expansion.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] Apart from improving access to contraception globally, furthering gender equality also has a great benefit.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] When women have the same education (decision-making power), this generally leads to smaller families.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] It is argued that the effects of habitat loss and fragmentation can be counteracted by including spatial processes in potential restoration management plans.
[src:habitat-destruction/habitat-destruction] However, even though spatial dynamics are incredibly important in the conservation and recovery of species, a limited amount of management plans are taking the spatial effects of habitat restoration and conservation into consideration.
